<HEADLINE> Somali Street Children Given Means to Earn Bread </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 13 (Xinhua) -- It has been a delightful
week for the shoe-shines in the Somali capital Mogadishu this
week.
</P>
<P>
About a hundred boxes, hundreds of brushes, wax and other
shoe-shine polishes have been distributed to nearly a hundred
street children in Mogadishu by Elman Peace Foundation Center
(EPFC),a local peace promoting agency.
</P>
<P>
According to Sudan Ali Ahmed, director of the center, the
children were summoned from the streets for the distribution of
these materials. "No Begging, Yes Work" were printed on top of
the small boxes that were distributed to the children whose age
varied between 9 and 15.
</P>
<P>
During the distribution which continued for two consecutive
days, Ahmed told Xinhua that the distribution of these materials
were just a part of their yearly activities for supporting the
abandoned and orphaned children in the streets of the capital so
as to create some easy jobs for them in which they can earn their
daily lives.
</P>
<P>
Abdirizak Ali Osman, a 13-year-old boy, told Xinhua that he's
confident that he will be able to earn his daily bread with the
box he's given. Osman whose face shone with happiness after
receiving the box and wax said, he's all alone with no parents,
brothers or sisters.
</P>
<P>
"The last of my family was my father who never returned back
after leaving home during the height of the civil war six years
back," he said.
</P>
<P>
After the distribution ceremony which was also attended by
officers from the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) and
representatives from other 23 local humanitarian agencies, EPFC
officers led the people to four other places where it runs other
vital projects including a large school in which 1,200 students
are taught first aid, mechanic, automobile driving, typing and
other basic knowledge such as arithmetic and English for the
daily use.
</P>
<P>
About 100 former militiamen demobilized and trained by EPFC
are also operating six big electric generators which give
electricity to residential areas in major parts of Hodon, Bulo
Hubey and Zone-K of South Mogadishu. These militiamen live on the
revenue they collect from these generators are now on the
self-sustenance stage.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed, brother of late Elman Ali Ahmed (Somalia's peace
activist killed by Somali gunmen in south Mogadishu in March
1996), also pledged the activities of his late brother will never
die.
</P>
<P>
He said he will continue the peace campaign by teaching and
demobilizing armed militiamen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
