<HEADLINE> Thai Woman Lifter Breaks World record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 13 (xinhua) -- Thailand's Suta Khassaraporn
broke a clean and jerk world record in the women's weightlifting
59-kg division on the third day of the Southeast Asian Games on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Suta lifted 125 kilograms to beat the previous mark of 124
kilograms set by Xiu Xiongying of China in Warsaw, Poland, last
year.
</P>
<P>
She already had the overall gold medal secured when her coach
told her to attack the world record.
</P>
<P>
Suta successfully lifted 92.5 kg in the snatch and her 122.5
kilograms in her second lift of the clean and jerk equaled her
previous best and put her far ahead of her rivals.
</P>
<P>
Her total lifting of 217.5 kilograms also broke the SEA Games
record of 210 kg.
</P>
<P>
"I never imagined I would break the world record before but I
always try to do my best," Suta said. "I've been lifting well in
training, from 125 to 127."
</P>
<P>
Her coach, Chang Mei Han, won three world titles in the 85
kilogram and over class for China from 1987-89.
</P>
<P>
The International Olympic Committee decided this year to
include women weightlifters in the games for the first time in
Sydney in 2000.
</P>
<P>
"I want to take part in the Olympics once in my life," Suta
said. "I haven't been focusing on the Olympics, but if I get there
I will just try my hardest again."  
</P>
</TEXT>
