<HEADLINE> Africa Needs Trained Army Forces, Says S. African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Although the threat of global
nuclear war has receded, there still remains a number of
potentially explosive situations that could erupt and threaten
world peace, visiting South African Defence Minister Joe Modise
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Modise said it is such potentially explosive situations that
make it increasingly important for the Southern African region to
train its respective forces in specialised peacekeeping and peace
support operations.
</P>
<P>
The South African minister was opening a two-week long
peacekeeping course at Zimbabwe's army headquarters in Harare
being attended by military officers from Zimbabwe, Namibia,
Botswana, Malawi, Lesotho, South Africa, Tanzania, Mauritius and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
In Africa, he noted, the threat to peace mainfested itself in
the form of unemployment, poverty, hunger and disease, lack of
democratic cultures in some countries, the burden of refugees,
drug smuggling and inter-ethnic or religious conflicts.
</P>
<P>
He said: ''Any one, or a combination of these threats to
stability, could spill over borders and require some form of
military intervention in the shape of peacekeeping.''
</P>
<P>
The instabilities highlighted made it mandatory for the region
to be prepared as it might be requested to participate in
peacekeeping operations by the OAU and the U.N., he said.
</P>
<P>
Joint peace support exercise like exercise Blue Hungwe hosted
by Zimbabwe this year helped strengthen the region's capacity to
respond to such operations, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said: ''We have a need, therefore, for more
modern weaponry, especially for land, sea and air operations
particularly where a peace support requirement arises which
demands a conventional warfare.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
