<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NASA Postpones Saturn Probe Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National
Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) today decided to delay
the launch of its Saturn probe, Cassini, due to strong wind and
technical problems.
</P>
<P>
NASA said that it would try again to launch the craft, powered
by 72 pounds of highly radioactive plutonium no earlier than
Wednesday in Cape Canaveral, Florida.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled launch of the Titan 4-B rocket holding the
Cassini spacecraft was pushed back first by technical trouble,
then by stiff wind at high altitudes and other difficulties,
according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
As the countdown dragged on, a computer problem cropped up with
Cassini and NASA called everything off.
</P>
<P>
Cassini's destination, eventually, is the ringed planet Saturn.
The trip, by way of Venus, Earth and Jupiter for gravity-assisted
speed, will take seven years and cover 3.52 billion km.
</P>
<P>
The entire mission, NASA's largest, most expensive
interplanetary probe ever, will last 11 years and cost 3.4 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
As the craft carries the most plutonium ever, anti-nuclear
activists feared that a launch accident would cause the
carcinogenic plutonium to rain down.
</P>
<P>
Cassini will swoop within 900 km of Earth after having swung
past Venus twice. The spacecraft won't reach Saturn until 2004;
the plutonium is needed to power all the instruments so far from
the sun.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Energy Department and NASA had 34 radiation-monitoring
teams stationed throughout the region to prove that residents were
in no danger in case the rocket exploded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
