<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Besieged Tobacco Leads to $32 Billion Merger Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Britain's B.A.T. Industries,
the world's second largest cigarette manufacturer, is discussing
with Zurich Group for a 32 billion U.S. dollar merger to get rid
of its burdensome link with the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
B.A.T. has decided to let the tobacco portion to survive on its
own and fold the U.S. and British insurance companies into the
financial businesses owned by Zurich Group, the New York Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
There has been relentless litigation over smoking deaths in the
United States and the dispute might be settled in payment of 368
billion dollars over 25 years by the U.S. tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
The stock price of B.A.T., whose tobacco fame concedes only to
the world top cigarette manufacturer Philip Morris companies of
the U.S., has failed to reflect normal valuations for insurance
and financial services companies, its officials complained.
</P>
<P>
The merger plan, acknowledged by relevant parties, may allow
Zurich Group to own 55 percent stake and B.A.T the rest. With a
combined market value of 32 billion dollars, it will be one of the
world's biggest mergers so far, the Times said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
