<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aid for Victims of Terrorism in Egypt Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri has decided to issue an urgent financial aid to the
families of the victims killed in the bloodiest attacks against
the police this year, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,000 Egyptian Pounds (about 885 U.S. dollars) will be
given to each family of the 11 people killed in two separate
terrorist attacks today in Minya, about 230 kilometers south of
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, who communicated the decision by telephone
to Minya governorate Moustafa Abdel Qader, also asked him to put
up marquees at the government's expense to receive people who will
call on the families of the victims to offer condolences.
</P>
<P>
Unidentified gunmen opened fire on policemen in patrols at
Malawi and Abu Korkas in stations in Minya, killing eight
policemen and three civilians and wounding one woman, according to
an Interior Ministry source.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen escaped and there is no immediate claim of
responsibility for the attack, which is bloodiest against the
security forces this year.
</P>
<P>
It was unclear so far if the two attacks, taking place within
30 minutes, were coordinated and carried out by the same group of
gunmen. Minya Security authorities began investigations into the
killings.
</P>
<P>
Minya, the Upper Egyptian governorate, is notorious for
frequent terrorist attacks in the past five years that targeted
the security forces.
</P>
<P>
In the latest terrorist attack in Minya, suspected Muslim
militants beheaded a policeman and shot dead a farmer in
two separate attacks on September 30.
</P>
<P>
The latest deaths brought to 1,255 the number of people killed
in Egypt since Muslim extremists began an anti-government campaign
in March 1992.
</P>
<P>
The government had declared victory in its five-year war
against Islamic militants just before September 18 when a German
tourist bus was blasted in downtown Cairo, which is believed to
upset the purported image of Egypt as a safe tourist heaven.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
