<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syndicate Smuggles Sugar into Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 13 (Xinhua) -- An international sugar
syndicate is flooding Kenya with untaxed sugar, denying the
government millions of shillings in revenue in a complex import
and export sugar racket, local sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The group with bases in Dubai, Mombasa, London and Nairobi
operates from fictitious clearing houses using offshore sugar
plants to rip the country of tax revenue while making in return
billions of tax-free money in sugar sales, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Upwards of some 30,000 tons of illegal sugar are imported into
Kenya every two weeks and are sneaked through the customs as
"goods on transit" to the Preferential Taxation Area (PTA) member
countries.
</P>
<P>
Some of the sugar is recorded from the transit points as
"industrial wares" from donor countries while others are merely
marked "on transit" to PTA countries as agricultural produce and
spares.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Kenya Revenue Authority and the Kenya Sugar
Authority have been cowed by the sugar barons who claim to have
"state immunity".
</P>
<P>
The sugar barons have even gone ahead to dupe the PTA by
setting up an offshore "sugar factory", where tons of the
imported sugar from Brazil and Europe are stocked before they are
shipped into Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The offshore sugar company has been set up just to defraud the
government and hoodwink inspectors to avoid paying duty levied on
non-PTA members. PTA has its preferential rates paid on
commodities imported from members states.
</P>
<P>
From January to August, the Kenyan government lost a colossal
sum of money through the importation of over 11,000 tons of sugar
into the country, said the sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
