<HEADLINE> New Development Corridors Planned in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe plans to have more
development corridors linking it with South Africa and the
Democratic Republic of Congo, Industry and Commerce Minister
Nathan Shamuyarira said today.
</P>
<P>
The corridors, which are transport and communications
passageways supposed to be incubators for economic development,
are in addition to the Beira Development Corridor between
Zimbabwe and Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The minister told participants to a one-day workshop on
Zimbabwe-Japan economic relations that the Zimbabwean government
is also looking at the Beitbridge-Gwanda-Bulawayo Corridor to
increase cooperation with South Africa on mining in the Limpopo
Valley and in tourism.
</P>
<P>
The third corridor from Harare to the Democratic Republic of
Congo through Zambia would be used to mobilize resources from in
and outside the country.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We are looking at a corridor that will have lines of
communication like railway lines, road and telecommunications
alongside tourism and mining."
</P>
<P>
He said, "We are inviting Japanese companies and entrepreneurs
to join us in our country's industrialization." Zimbabwe has two
Japanese companies currently involved in the country's motor
industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the southern African area, with a population of 175
million people, is a new growth area to which the Japanese should
respond and support. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
