<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Norwegian Government Submits 1998 Fiscal Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 13 (Xinhua)--The Norwegian government
submitted today to the parliament a tight budget proposal for 1998
in an effort to dampen the continued strong growth in the
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian economy is in its fifth consecutive year of
steady growth. Mainland GDP, which excludes the petroleum and
shipping sector, accounts for about 85 percent of the total GDP
and is estimated to grow by 3.5 percent this year and 3 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
The total GDP is estimated to grow by 3.9 percent in 1997 and
4.6 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The growth is broadly based, with private consumption and
investment as the main driving forces. The export growth will
remain strong. Unemployment is estimated at 4.2 percent in 1997
and 3.8 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Expenditure will grow by 1 percent in real terms from 1997 to
1998. The growth in expenditure is mainly caused by increased
investments in the provision of care for the aged and of health
services.
</P>
<P>
The government also proposes to increase the allocation of
funds for priority areas like the primary school reform, child
care and foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian monetary policy will continue to be oriented
towards maintaining a stable krone exchange rate against European
currencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
