<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: UK Economy Back on More Balanced Path </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Britain's economy has been back
on a more balanced and sustainable path as the latest balance of
payments figures revealed healthy surplus on the current account
in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
The second quarter's current account surplus of 0.9 billion
pounds (1.44 billion US dollars) was much larger than expected,
although smaller than the first quarter's surplus of 1.5 billion
pounds (2.4 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Over the Summer months, there has been a concern of a gap
between the strong consumer spending and the sluggish industrial
activities in Britain.
</P>
<P>
However, apart from the healthy balance of payment, the last
few weeks have seen some positive signs that the gap is starting
to narrow, and Britain's economy is back on a more balanced and
sustainable path.
</P>
<P>
Two months ago, the manufacturing sector looked in clear danger
of dipping back into recession, with the official figures
revealing a small fall in output in second quarter and another
fall in the third quarter looking a real possibility.
</P>
<P>
However, manufacturing output is now estimated to have grown by
0.6 percent over the last three months and by around 2 percent
compared to a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The prospects for the manufacturing sector going forward have
been improved by the slip in the exchange rate over the last
several months prompted initially by the Bank of England's hints
that interest rates are on hold for a while.
</P>
<P>
At the same time as the danger of recession in industry appears
to have eased, there have been hints that the consumer sector is
starting to lose a little heat.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey from the Bank of England and MORI suggested
that the majority of windfall-induced spending may now have taken
place, with about 5 billion pounds (8 billion US dollars) of the
payouts having been spent by August.
</P>
<P>
There are also tentative signs that the recent base rate hikes
may be starting to have an impact. In particular, the housing
market recovery may now be starting to show the strain of the
recent increases in mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the Bank of England reveal that the total number
of net new mortgage commitments fell to 103,000 in August, the
lowest level since March.
</P>
<P>
However, financial experts here believe that for the time
being, the consumer sector has enough momentum to ensure that any
slowdown is too little and too late to prevent interest rates from
rising again over the next month or two.
</P>
<P>
While Britain's economy is now on its way to the balance, the
strong sterling in foreign exchange markets remains a headache for
its economy.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that even after its recent fall, the
pound is up by nearly 20 percent in a year suggests that it must
now be over-valued.
</P>
<P>
They warn that the current level, if sustained, will do great
damage to British industry, possibly even bringing another
recession. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
