<HEADLINE> 4,000 Diamond Miners Banned in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Over 4,000 small-scale miners
in northwest Tanzania's Shinyanga District, have been ordered to
stop mining diamond at Maganzo Village.
</P>
<P>
The miners, who were accused of causing serious environmental
destruction to the village's arable land since last year, have been
ordered to stop mining activities immediately and cover all pits in
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The ban, effective last Saturday, was given by the Shinyanga
District Commissioner, Simon Massaga, Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
The district commissioner said that unlicensed miners have illegally
excavated over 10,000 mining pits at the village which are likely to
become breeding grounds of communicable diseases such as cholera and
dysentery in the coming rainy season.
</P>
<P>
Messaga told the newspaper that over 90 percent of the estimated
5,000 hectares of the village farmland have been destroyed by the
miners who came from various areas.
</P>
<P>
As a result, over 2,000 families have been made landless and the
villagers are likely to experience hunger next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Messaga also expressed great concern over the villagers' decision
to even offer some of the living rooms and backyards to take up the
mining activities.
</P>
<P>
He said several houses have collapsed and others may fall down
during rainy season as their foundations have been loosened.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Massaga said 55 people have been booked by the police
and were brought to court last week for engaging in mining activities
inside Mwadui Diamond Company mining area charged with trespassing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
