<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Botswana Makes First Ever Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Air Botswana, the national
airline in Botswana, made a profit for the first time this year since
its inception in 1981, reporting 3.020 billion Pula (808 million U.S.
Dollars) for the year to March 31, according to sources reaching here
today.
</P>
<P>
"It's a modest one at this stage, but it shows that we have turned
the corner," Air Botswana General Manager Joshua Galeforolwe said.
</P>
<P>
Air Botswana recorded a loss of 18.655 billion Pula (4.96 billion
dollars) in 1993. Losses dropped steadily to 1.875 billion Pula (499
million dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
Galeforolwe attributes the recovery to "restructuring,recapitalization
and rationalization".
</P>
<P>
Air Botswana owns two aircraft and leases a third. The core route
remains between Gaborone, the capital of Botswana, and Johannesburg,
a commercial and trade center in South Africa, and customers are
mainly business people.
</P>
<P>
These passengers are "high yield, less price sensitive and
non-seasonal", Galeforolwe said. The airline is now targeting state
officials to get them out of cars and on to planes, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia's Supreme Court Rejects Appeal to Free </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Supreme Court
of Ethiopia today ruled out the appeal by lawyers either for the
dismissal of the case against former Deputy Prime Minister
Tamirat Layne and his accomplices or their acquittal, the
Ethiopian News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme court, citing article 63 of the procedural law of
the Penal Code, said it has no mandate to grant bail to a
defendant who might face a rigorous imprisonment of about 15
years.
</P>
<P>
The court ordered the prosecutor to present evidences upto
October 15 to the registrar's office.
</P>
<P>
At today's hearing, the report said, the court underlined the
need to comply with its decisions on the part of the prosecutor
and mentioned that it would be forced to take legal measures on
conditions that the prosecutor fails to willingfully discharge
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
Tamirat, who was relieved of his post of Deputy Prime Minister
and defense minister for disciplinary reasons in October 1996,
has been charged with three counts of abuse of power and holding
11 million dollars in foreign banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
