<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Moslems Urged to Join in Anti-Polio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Minister of Health
Adem Ibrahim today called on the Moslem clerics to mobilize
the faithful for the implementation of the national polio
immunization campaign.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting here on the National Polio Immunization
Days, the minister pointed out that religious groups are duty-bound
both morally and spiritually to promote the health conditions
of their faithfuls.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, he said they should sensitize the public to have
their children vaccinated in two rounds immunization campaign this
year throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, representative of the World Health Organization
Bernard Moriener said the active participation of the Moslem
community and that of all other religious groups is essential to
the success of the polio eradication campaign in the country.
</P>
<P>
He noted that close to 8.6 million children under five years of
age will be inoculated against polio during this year's national
polio immunization days in ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
There will be 25,000 vaccination posts with approximately
75,000 health workers and volunteers, he said, adding that 20
million doses of the vaccine and 25,000 vaccine carriers have
been imported from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
During the second round of the campaign, in addition to the
polio vaccine, the children will also receive one dose of vitamin
which significantly reduces the frequency of blindness and child
mortality rate, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia plans to eradicate polio by the year 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
