<HEADLINE> Jordan Slackens Security Ties With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Deputy Prime
Minister Jawad Anani said today that Jordan had slackened its
security cooperation with Israel over the Mashaal affair.
</P>
<P>
Anani said in an interview with Israel Radio that security
staff in Israeli Embassy in Amman had been decreased at Jordan's
request following the assassination attempt of Khaled Mashaal, a
Hamas leader in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the number of security staff in the Israeli Embassy
has decreased as a result of that thing. So this is the indicator
of the slackening of security cooperation in that area," he said.
</P>
<P>
Three agents of Mossad, Israeli intelligence service, attempted
on September 25 to kill Mashaal outside his Amman office. But the
operation failed and two of the agents were arrested by the
Jordanian police and confessed their identities.
</P>
<P>
Anani accused Israel of violating the peace treaty signed in
1994 between the two countries, stressing that Jordan was angered
by the Israeli move which he said infringed the kingdom's
sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
But he expressed belief that despite the Mashaal affair, the
bilateral relations would return to normal. He disclosed that
Jordan had received Israel's assurances that such incident would
never occur again.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Anani slammed Israel for its hesitation in
implementing the peace treaty, including blocking Jordan's trade
with the Palestinian National Authority, delaying the construction
of a joint airport in the Red Sea port city of Aqaba and joint
development of the Jordan Valley.
</P>
<P>
To mend the bilateral ties, Israeli cabinet decided on Sunday
to accelerate the negotiation pace of the construction of the
Aqaba airport.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai said
today that he expected to visit Jordan shortly in a bid to amend
the ties.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in the Knesset (Parliament), Mordechai
praised King Hussein and Jordanian government for promoting peace
with Israel, adding that he was optimistic about the resumption of
full security cooperation with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
"I think Jordan and Israel have highly intention to continue
the peace. I'm looking forward, in a very short time, to visit
Jordan to continue negotiation and cooperation on all security
subjects," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
