<HEADLINE> UK's PM Meets Sinn Fein Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 13 (Xinhua) - British Prime Minister Tony Blair
met Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams today, the first encounter
between a British prime minister and Irish Republican leader since
1921, according to reports from Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Blair's decision to meet Adams has drawn fierce criticism from
Northern Irish Protestant leaders and political opponents in
London.
</P>
<P>
David Trimble, the Ulster Unionist Party leader, expressed pity
for a prime minister to meet the head of "a terrorist
organization" that had killed so many British soldiers, policement
and civilians and had still not forsworn violence.
</P>
<P>
Tony Blair defended his meeting with Adams by saying that
"genuine progress" was being made towards a lasting political
settlement.
</P>
<P>
All parties in the peace talks had a "great degree of common
ground", he added.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the meeting, Adams said he hoped the
Northern Ireland peace process would lead to a united Ireland.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped that Tony Blair would be the last British Prime
Minister with jurisdiction over the province.
</P>
<P>
The Sinn Fein leader hailed the meeting as "the best
opportunity for peace and to bring about justice and freedom".
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein was granted entry to the talks for the first time
last Tuesday when they resumed after a Summer recess because the
IRA had called a ceasefire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
