<HEADLINE> Fighting Goes On in S. Leone Despite Call for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Fighting continued today in Sierra
Leone between the west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) and
soldiers loyal to the military junta despite plans to resume talks on
resolving crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
While attacking an ECOMOG military base near the capital Freetown
in the past three days, the junta took similar actions against ECOMOG
bases in the southeast towns of Bo and Kenema, the British
Broadcasting Corporation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The junta troops started in the early hours of Saturday to attack
an ECOMOG base in a town several miles from Bo, the second largest
city of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Fighting went on through Saturday and Sunday, and again this
morning, with intermittent firing and heavy explosions.
</P>
<P>
Around 11:00 this morning, a Nigerian jet flew over and dropped
three or four bombs at the junta soldiers.
</P>
<P>
However, each time the soldiers launched attack over the past three
days, they had been driven off and the base has still in the hand of
ECOMOG, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, a number of ECOMOG positions in this area
are believed to be small, probably around 300 and may be supported by
the Kamajors, a group of traditional hunters fighting to restore
ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Total casualty of the junta soldiers is not yet known but the
report said six dead bodies have so far been brought into the hospital
in Bo, along with the injured.
</P>
<P>
Reinforcements are also reported to have been brought in on Sunday
to help the attacks.
</P>
<P>
There are similar attacks in Kenema to the northeast of Bo but the
junta soldiers have failed to take the ECOMOG position there.
</P>
<P>
The junta claimed at the weekend that it had overrun a Nigerian
military base outside Freetown and captured some Nigerian soldiers,
who constitute the bulk of ECOMOG forces.
</P>
<P>
Describing the claim as "wishful thinking", ECOMOG said it still
held the position allegedly overrun by the junta.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG accused that the junta attacked the base aiming at holding
hostage soldiers and civilians taking refuge there as human shield and
using them to bargain in future negotiations for the return of rebel
leader Foday Sanko.
</P>
<P>
West African countries decided on Saturday to resume dialogue with
the junta toward peaceful settlement of the crisis in Sierra Leone
triggered off by the the May 25 coup that toppled the legitimate
government led by President Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Before they made the decision, west African foreign ministers had a
three-hour "very useful" closed-door meeting with Sankoh, who has been
detained in Nigeria since last March.
</P>
<P>
The junta has been demanding Sankoh to be sent back to Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
So far there has no response from the junta toward the re-opening
of the negotiation it has asked for.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
