<HEADLINE> Greek Defense Minister Accuses Turkey of "Wasting Time" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos today accused Turkey of wasting its time in
infringing Athens flight information region (FIR) and calling into
doubt Greece's sovereign rights.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on the sidelines of the NATO military
exercise "Dynamic Mix'97 " which ends today near Thessaloniki,
Tsohatzopoulos said that Turkey was wasting its energy and putting
the lives of its pilots in "unnecessary danger."
</P>
<P>
He urged Turkey to realize that its interest lay in
strengthening "domestic stability" and its relations with the
European Union (EU) by developing good neighborly relations and
recognizing the principles and values that all U.N. member states
were obliged to accept in practice.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Greek military exercise "Toxotis" and the
Cypriot exercise "Nikiforos" are under way in the southeastern
Aegean.
</P>
<P>
Athens claimed that a large number of Turkish jet fighters
infringed the Athens FIR in the same area and violated Greek and
Cyprus airspace over the past two days.
</P>
<P>
The exercises confirmed the two countries' joint defense
doctrine, he said, adding that no one could prevent them from
successfully conducting these exercises.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greek government spokesman Dimitris
Reppas said today that Turkey's attitude would not change Greece's
policy.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's position was making its relations with Greece and its
course towards the international community more difficult, he
said.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that Greek-Turkish rapprochement would be
meaningful only on the basis of rules and, in that sense, if
Turkey conformed, a meeting between the two countries' prime
ministers in Crete on the sidelines of the two-day Balkan summit
starting on november 3 could serve as "an opportunity for a new
rapprochement." 
</P>
</TEXT>
