<HEADLINE> Greek Defense Minister Visits Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos arrived here today to demonstrate his country's
staunch support for the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon his arrival at Larnaca Airport this afternoon,
Tsohatzopoulos said "we have big challenges ahead of us and we
must be optimistic that we can make next year the year of big
positive changes in the Cyprus problem."
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus affair has remained unresolved since 1974 when
Turkey sent troops to the island following a failed pro-Athens
coup. Effort are now underway to bring together the Greek
Cypriot-controlled south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north.
</P>
<P>
Attacking Turkey as a "destabilizing factor," the Greek
minister said "Turkey is accountable for the continuing occupation
of part of the Republic of Cyprus and Turkish threats for the use
of force are nothing more than attempts to legalize the status
quo."
</P>
<P>
Turkey maintains 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus, which was
declared by Turkish Cypriots in 1983 as the "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus," recognized only by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos said the recent Turkish warplanes' violations of
Greek and Cypriot airspace were part of its offensive designs
against Greece and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Athens said that it has recorded more than 60 violations by
Ankara's jetfighters Sunday and Monday as the Greek-Cypriot joint
military exercises were going on and nearly all the violators were
intercepted by Greek jets.
</P>
<P>
"We are strong enough to ensure that Turkey's designs will not
get through," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos came to Cyprus to review the final stage of the
ongoing Greek Cypriot National Guard annual military exercises
code-named "Nikiforos (Victorious) '97."
</P>
<P>
The five-day military exercises, in its fourth day today, are
participated by the Greece's air and naval forces.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos will join Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides to
review a military parade in Larnaca at the end of the maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed a defense pact in November 1993,
under which the Greek armed forces will provide Cyprus with
assistance in case the island is attacked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
