<HEADLINE> France to Partly Privatize Defense Electronics Giant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The French government decided
today to sell 20 percent of the shares of the state-owned defense
and electronics giant, Thomson CSF, to Alcatel Alsthom
telecommunications group and the Dassault Electronics group.
</P>
<P>
The deal will bring 35 billion francs (about 6 billion US
dollars) of income to the French government, said French
officials.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned Aerospatiale airspace group, which makes Airbus
passenger planes, will also share part of the stocks of the
Thomson CSF by joining the latter in producing satellites, said
the government.
</P>
<P>
The government will keep 35 percent of the shares of Thomson
CSF, which is the largest defense electronics group in Europe and
the third largest in the world after the U.S. groups of
Lockheed-Martin and Hughes-Raytheon.
</P>
<P>
The government now has 58 percent of the shares of Thomson CSF,
while 42 percent other shares are in the hands of other public
entities.
</P>
<P>
"This restructuring will allow the gathering of the French
competences in several fields, contribute to the development of
synergy between the civil and military applications of strategic
electronics and reinforce the potentials of research-development
of Thomson CSF abd Alcatel-Alsthom," said a communique issued by
the office of Prime Minister Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
Both Alcatel and Dassault hailed the decision, describing it as
the ``best choice for a common success'' which will reinforce
France's capability in civil and military aeronautics and space
industry.
</P>
<P>
Alcatel Alsthom group is the world's fourth largest producer of
telecommunications equipments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
