<HEADLINE> Arafat Calls for Speedy Transfer of PNA Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat today in Gaza urged
Israel to speed up the transfer of the taxes owed to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters after his meeting with Israeli
ex-coordinator of negotiations with the PNA Aron Shahor, Arafat
accused Israel of not fulfilling its promise made in the past
despite his recent secret talks with Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
During today's meeting, Arafat and Shahor discussed the latest
developments of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said that nothing special has been offered so far by
the Israeli side to the peace process although his talks with
Netanyahu were "good."
</P>
<P>
Israel has frozen the transfer of tax revenues to the PNA
following the July 30 suicide bombings in Jerusalem which killed
18 people and injured 151 others. PNA officials said that Israel
so far has transferred about 40 percent of the total revenue to
the PNA, and the remaining 110 million U.S. dollars are still in
Israeli hands.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Netanyahu met last Wednesday at Erez checkpoint
between Jerusalem and the Gaza Strip and the two discussed ways
and means for reviving the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In another development, over 1,000 Palestinian young people
and college students demonstrated today in the West Bank city of
Nablus to protest against the Israeli occupation and closure of
the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators, some of them waving Palestinian flags and
assault rifles, pledged to rally around Arafat and fight to the
end against the Israeli occupation. 
</P>
