<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hyacinth in Zambian River Threatens Life of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Hyacinth is threatening a new
bridge in Kafue river of Zambia, an environmental official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Inspector of natural resources of the Environmental Council of
Zambia (ECZ), Willy Kalunga, said that the weed is spreading at a fast
rate exerting pressure on the new bridge, thereby shortening its life
span.
</P>
<P>
He said unless something is done immediately to bring the weed
under control other infrastructures such as the Kafue Gorge dam walls,
the rail bridge and the water works facilities along the river might
be affected.
</P>
<P>
He said the Environment Ministry in conjunction with ECZ, the
National Council for Scientific Research and the University of
Zambia will spray chemicals to supplement the biological method
to control the weed.
</P>
<P>
Kalunga said in 1995, the ECZ tried to control the weed using the
weevils but that these have resorted to eating reeds instead of the
weeds.
</P>
<P>
He said it is difficult to control the weed because it doubles
itself every fortnight.
</P>
<P>
It is said that five square meters of the weed exerts pressure
equal to one tone of weight on each of the bridge's pillars.
</P>
<P>
The weed is clogging the river, Zambia's lifeblood for water
resources. The river from its upper reaches in the Northwestern
Province down to its confluence with the great Zambezi river in the
South also supports a great deal of Zambia's economic activity like
agriculture, fishery and power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
