<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Confirmed as CDU Chancellor Candidate for Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LEIPZIG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
was confirmed today by his ruling Christian Democratic Union (CDU)
party as its chancellor candidate for the next general election
due in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the national congress of the CDU in the eastern
German city of Leipzig, Kohl announced the start of the election
campaign and called on party members to firmly united behind him
in order to defeat the main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD)
again next year.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, who has been in office for uninterrupted 15 years,
already ranks as Europe's longest-serving political leader and as
the most durable German chancellor this century.
</P>
<P>
He stressed today that he felt obliged to seek another term to
guide Germany into the next century which is full of challenges.
</P>
<P>
"What I want to do is to take responsibility and do my duty. For
this reason, I will again be the chancellor candidate," Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
His 90-minute speech was received by long-time applauses and
standing ovations from the 1.001 delegates, some of whom had until
recently been challenging Kohl's leadership.
</P>
<P>
During his speech, Kohl also branded the main opposition Social
Democrats (SPD) as a party of outmoded ideas, which could not
properly follow the great changes at the end of the 20th century
and wanted to block key reforms needed to keep the country
competitiveness in a world of globalization.
</P>
<P>
"If we did not make preparations for the next century, we would
be left behind by the development," Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that if re-elected, he would again make it a top
priority to push through his failed tax reform which had been
designed to bolster business confidence, investment and hiring.
</P>
<P>
Predicting that the German economy was set to grow between 2.8
and three percent this year instead of the 2.5 percent growth
predicted earlier, Kohl also cautioned that economic growth alone
would not be enough to bring down the country's record high
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
"We must stress both: growth and structural reforms," he said.
</P>
<P>
On foreign policy issues, Kohl reiterated his commitment to the
planned single European currency, the Euro. "We will make sure
that the Euro will come punctually and as a stable currency, with
strict adherence to the legally binding criteria," he said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the leadership issue, the three-day CDU congress
will also adopt a working agenda for the period until 2002 which
will center on employment, crime, education and Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
