<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Reduces Malawians' Life Span </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- AIDS will further reduce
Malawians' average life span to 44 years by 2010 from current 45
if its spread remains unchecked, the World Bank has said.
</P>
<P>
According to its latest assessment of the impact of disease on
the country, about 13 percent of Malawi's population has been
infected with the HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The current life span could be 57 years if Aids is put under
control, said the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
In the absence of disease, the current population of about 10
million will increase to 16.7 million in the year 2010, said the
study of the bank.
</P>
<P>
By July of this year more than 50,000 Aids cases had been
reported to National Aids Control Program and the actual number
of cases is much higher than the reported cases, it said.
</P>
<P>
At the root of the problem is the high rate of sexually
transmitted infections which account for the majority of the
HIV/AIDS cases in the country, the study said.
</P>
<P>
Malawian Health Minister Harry Thompson was quoted as saying
that the Malawian government will do its utmost to protect those
who have not contracted the disease but people should change
their behavior or the efforts will be useless.
</P>
<P>
Last year 10.5 million U.S. dollars was spent on Aids in the
country and more than 95 of the money came from foreign donors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
