<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Singer John Denver Dies in Plane Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- American singer John Denver,
whose songs "Rocky Mountain High" and "Take Me Home, Country
Roads" gained worldwide appeal, died in a single-engine plane
crash Sunday in California.
</P>
<P>
Denver was piloting the two-seat experimental plane that
suddenly nose-dived and smashed into Monterey Bay. The body was
recovered Sunday from Monterey Bay, according to reports today.
</P>
<P>
The plane took off from Monterey Airport shortly after 5 p.m.
local time Sunday, with the first reports of crash at 5:27 p.m.
</P>
<P>
Denver established himself as a star in the 1970s with his
melodic, light folk-pop.
</P>
<P>
He scored hits with songs like "Sunshine on My Shoulders" and
"Thank God I'm a Country Boy" and was named Country Music
Entertainer of the Year in 1975.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen of his albums went gold and eight platinum, and he had
many gold and platinum sales overseas.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, he toured the Soviet Union to perform as a cultural
exchange between the United States and the Soviet Union. He became
the first artist from the West to do a multi-city tour of China in
October 1992, and similarly in Vietnam in May 1994.
</P>
<P>
"Music does bring people together," Denver once said. "No
matter what language we speak, what color we are, the form of our
politics or the expression of our love and our faith, music
proves: We are the same."
</P>
<P>
In 1976, Denver co-founded the Windstar Foundation, a
non-profit environmental education and research center that works
toward a sustainable future for the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
