<HEADLINE> France's Top Boss Resigns to Protest 35 Hour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- In a dramatic showdown with the
Socialist government of Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, Jean
Gandois, the president of France's national employers' association
CNPF, resigned today to protest the plan of Jospin to reduce
workweek time to 35 hours from the year 2,000.
</P>
<P>
Jospin announced the plan last Friday at the national jobs
conference, which were attended by Gandois and representatives of
trade unions.
</P>
<P>
Gandois, who was the first man to resign from the presidency of
CNPF in the group's 50-year history, said later that he became the
victim of a "conspiracy" between Jospin and union leaders, who
he said "fooled" him by asking him to attend the conference and
then telling him about their plan on 35 hours.
</P>
<P>
In a bitter statement issued today after announcing his
resignation, Gandois said that he quit the job because he was
"more a negotiator than a killer."
</P>
<P>
He said the 35-hour plan would harm the competitiveness of
France's enterprises, "condemn the bosses," deteriorate France's
unemployment, harm European construction, and suspend the dialogue
between employers and employees.
</P>
<P>
Gandois also predicted a ``hard battle'' between the bosses and
the Socialist government over the 35-hour plan.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would continue to fight against the plan in
order to let "the corporate spirit triumph and let the country
escape the danger of ideologies and intolerance."
</P>
<P>
The government refused to comment on his resignation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
