<HEADLINE> Washington State to Vote Gun Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Voters in the Western state of
Washington of the United States will have a say next month on
whether a gun control initiative should become law.
</P>
<P>
The state's decision to put the gun control measure before
voters came amid high accidental shooting incidence and strong gun
lobby activities in the Capital Hill, the New York Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The proposal would require handgun owners to pass a safety test
to obtain a license to possess a gun and all pistols to be sold
with trigger-locking devices, the Times said.
</P>
<P>
"If we were to pass an initiative of the people that bypassed
the gun lobby and did so in a Western state, it would be truly
historic," an initiative advocate was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The state government estimates that nearly one in five people
in a population of 5.5 million own handguns.
</P>
<P>
Washington is among the country's eight states where more
people are killed by guns every year than in car accidents.
</P>
<P>
The rate of people killed by accidental shooting in Washington
is 4.5 times higher than that of the 25 leading industrial nations
combined and the overall rate for the U.S. is nine times higher
than the other countries combined, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"Backed by a Congress that has blocked any new restrictions on
personal firearms, gun supporters have found the nation's capital
to be a friendly place of late," it added.
</P>
<P>
The National Rifle Association, which campaigns against gun
control, has said it would broadcast television advertisements
five times that the initiative supporters would do. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
