<HEADLINE> US Envoy Urges Cyprus Parties to Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. special envoy for Cyprus
Richard Holbrooke urged here today all parties concerned in
Cyprus to avoid actions which might increase tensions.
</P>
<P>
Following a two-hour meeting with Turkish Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem this afternoon, Holbrooke said holding military
exercises at this moment would not be conducive to the Cyprus
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Greek and Greek Cypriot troops are now conducting one-week
joint exercises, code-named "Nikiforos '97", in the Greek
Cypriot-controlled area.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke said that he had exchanged views with Cem over the
Cyprus situation and other related issues. But he declined to
disclose the contents of his talks with Cem, saying "confidential
talks have to remain confidential."
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem failed to turn out for
questions following the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke denied that he came to Ankara with a specified
peace plan from the White House and that the Cyprus issue is a
problem between the United States and Turkey, saying that Turkey
is a close ally of Washington.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy said that he and Thomas Miller, U.S. State
Department's new coordinator on Cyprus issue, came to Ankara
to find out Turkey's position on this issue.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke and Thomas arrived here Sunday on a shuttle mission
for the protracted Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Thomas will fly to Athens Tuesday to meet Greek leaders for
the Cyprus issue, said Holbrooke. It remains unclear when
Holbrooke will leave Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Holbrooke also met with Turkish President
Suleyman Demirel and Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz, who just
returned from Strasburg, France, for a council of Europe meeting.
</P>
<P>
Demirel has said that Turkey always supports a political
solution to the Cyprus issue, saying a bizonal and bicommunal
federation might be a settlement to the problem.
</P>
<P>
Following his meeting with Yilmaz, Holbrooke said that the
talks were positive, saying the U.S. government hopes that Greece
and Turkey improve their bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He added that he will meet Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash in New York later this month.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into rival Greek Cypriot community in
the south and Turkish Cypriot community in the north since 1974
when Turkish troops took over the northern third of the island in
the weak of an abortive coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The situation on the small eastern Mediterranean island has
become worse after the Cypriot government signed a deal to buy
anti-aircraft missiles from Russia in January.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and international community have been
making efforts for a peaceful solution to the thorny issue, but
no tangible results have been achieved so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
