<HEADLINE> Africa Faces Challenges of Educating Consumers: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior official from the
International Advertising Association (IAA) said here today that
educating consumers is vital to the ultimate success of the
health growth of the African economies.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the on-going Third Africa Congress of the IAA, IAA
World President Senyon Kim noted that Africa faced challenges to
educate consumers to the value and benefits of free market
economies.
</P>
<P>
He told the four-day meeting started here today that
advertising and marketing would be at the forefront of the
development of the African continent in the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
Advertising and marketing would go hand in hand with the
notion of a borderless continent, he said at the meeting which
has the theme "Creating a Borderless Continent: Africa's 21st
Century Communication Challenge".
</P>
<P>
The president pointed out that a borderless African continent
means borderless communications which is "a way to promote the
economies of Africa."
</P>
<P>
He explained that advertising is the vital conduit for that
information between producer and consumer and no one else has the
motivation to do it.
</P>
<P>
Advertising has so often been described as just the vested
interest of business, said Kim, adding that it has rarely been
seen as the voice of the free market economy and the servant of
the free-choosing consumer.
</P>
<P>
The IAA is the world's only partnership of advertisers,
agencies, media and specialized services. it has 3,700 senior
members and 1,000 associate members in 95 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
