<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Needs $1b to Repair Refineries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has to spend one billion U.S.
Dollars if it wants to put the four on-and-off refineries back in good
shape so as to eradicate haunting fuel scarcity, according to latest
studies.
</P>
<P>
The report of the technical assessment, carried out by oil
giants Mobil and Shell, is now being studied by the Nigerian
National Petroleum Corporation and the National Economic
Intelligence Committee.
</P>
<P>
The four refineries, three in the south and one in the north, were
built seven to 32 years ago, with total daily capacity of 445,000
barrels.
</P>
<P>
Because of the old age and the lack of regular maintenance for
fund shortage, most of the units of the four refineries are
either out of order or become obsolete, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the production has been reduced to half of their
capacity, which caused acute fuel scarcity that slowed down business
activities in many parts of the country between March and July this
year.
</P>
<P>
The government had to resort to import to ease the situation and
part of the foreign product were recently confirmed by Environmental
Protection Agency to be toxic, producing a bad odor hazardous to
people's health.
</P>
<P>
However, the deadline for importation, originally scheduled for
September, is expected to be extended beyond December this year as it
will take months to finish maintenance of a plant even though it
starts right at the moment.
</P>
<P>
It is the hope of Nigerians that the government shall take an early
decision for the repair job in order to put an end to fuel shortage
in this largest oil producing country of Africa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
