<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Unveils Rehabilitation Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government today
officially announced a comprehensive rehabilitation program as a
fresh bid to revive the country's troubled economy.
</P>
<P>
The program was unveiled as Thai Deputy Prime Minister
Virabongsa Ramangura, Finance Minister Thanong Bidaya and Bank of
Thailand Governor Chaiyawat Wibulsawasdi jointly held a press
conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The program will mainly focus on solving the problems facing
the financial sector, especially the 58 finance firms whose
operations were suspended by the government earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, Thailand will soon set a financial
restructuring agency and a financial management company to help
handle the problems of these finance firms.
</P>
<P>
The program will also allow foreign investors to hold a stake
of more than 50 percent in any of the troubled 58 finance firms
for a period up to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the program requires finance institutions in the
country to increase their capital to keep themselves stable, while
the government will push amendments of the related laws to enable
it to play a greater role in handling financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The rehabilitation program also covers many other fields,
including the introduction of significant measures to promote
exports, tourism and services businesses and reduce imports to
curb the country's inflation and the current account deficit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
