<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Announces Further Budget Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government today
approved a further cut in the 1998 fiscal budget by 100 billion
baht (2.75 billion U.S. dollars) to meet the demand of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) for support to help revive its
troubled economy.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Virabongsa Ramangkura announced the new
cut at a press conference today.
</P>
<P>
Plus an earlier cut of 59 billion baht (1.6 billion dollars),
the country's budget for fiscal 1998 has been reduced to 823
billion baht (22.64 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has been under pressure from the IMF to
reduce government spending and increase revenue in return for a
standby 17.2-billion-dollar credit to help Thailand revive its
ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
Today, the deputy prime minister also unveiled an economic
rehabilitation package which covers the restructuring of industry,
agriculture and services, and supporting introduction of new
technology, new management know-how, and privatization of state
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
If these measures are implemented strictly, Thailand's economic
growth for 1998 will be at 3.5 percent, and 6-7 percent in the
following two years, Virabongsa said.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate for this year is expected to be 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Current account deficit next year will drop to 3 percent of
gross domestic product from 5 percent this year under the rescue
plan.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, foreign exchange reserves will increase to 24-25
billion dollars from 23 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's fiscal 1998 began on October 1 this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria's Foreign Debts Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria's foreign debts have
dropped to their lowest level in 20 years, said Suranyi Gyorgy,
chief of the Bulgarian Nemzeti Bank.
</P>
<P>
Gyorgy said that by the end of last June, Bulgarian foreign
debts totalled 10.5 billion U.S. dollars. He predicted that by the
end of this year, the figure could be further reduced to 10
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In this way, Bulgaria would change from a heavily indebted
country into a middle-indebted country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Gyorgy also noted that the inflation rate had dropped from 23
percent to 18 percent, and probably to 17 percent by the end of
this year. Bulgaria will try to lower its inflation rate to less
than 10 percent when it enters the European Union in 2001- 2002.
</P>
<P>
He estimated this year's fiscal deficit at less than 1.7
billion U.S. dollars, accounting for 3.5 to 3.6 percent of the
gross domestic products (GDP) figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
