<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Faces up to Challenge of Information Age: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong has to face up to
the challenge of the information age in order to retain its
competitiveness in the new era, a senior official of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a reception marking the 125th anniversary of the
British company of Cable and Wireless, Donald Tsang, financial
secretary of the HKSAR, said that Hong Kong had a long history of
facing up to challenges and embracing new technology.
</P>
<P>
"From a policy perspective, the way Hong Kong is connected to
the rest of the world is a serious matter indeed," Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
"Questions arise at a very basic level: for example, what role
do we wish Hong Kong as an economy to play in future? How can we
best manage the transition of our community to an information
society? How can we assist our country, China, in considering
these issues?" Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government has determined to place priority on
addressing these questions, Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, Chief Executive of the HKSAR, expressed a vision
of Hong Kong assuming a leadership position in the information
industries in his first policy address delivered last week.
</P>
<P>
Tsang said the government must facilitate the establishment of
an open common interface information infrastructure and the laying
down of an appropriate regulatory framework to remove obstacles to
 interconnection.
</P>
<P>
The government should also develop a policy for promoting
information technology applications, Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
"The developments in the information industries are likely to
change the very way in which mankind lives and works and the way
business, trade and commerce are conducted globally," Tsang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
