<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Minister Urges Market Economy Recognization (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese minister of foreign
trade and economic co-operation Wu Yi today urged the European
Union (EU) to respect China's practical situation and remove the
country from EU's list of non-market economies at an early date.
</P>
<P>
The action of terming China as a non-market economy in
disregard of China's development is either out of prejudice or for
the deliberate purpose of confusing black with white, and will
seriously impede the further progress of Sino-European economic
and trade ties, Wu said in her talks with Leon Brittan,
vice-president of the EU Commission.
</P>
<P>
Brittan, who is here to discuss China-Europe relationship and
China's membership to the WTO, responded that it is incorrect to
describe today's China which is undergoing rapid economic growth
as a non-market economy.
</P>
<P>
EU emphasizes its relations with China both politically and
economically, and hopes to view China's progress in a practical
and friendly way, he said.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that as an EU official in charge of China affairs,
he will try all efforts to make EU member countries better
understand China.
</P>
<P>
Wu reaffirmed China's stress on its economic and trade
relations with EU. She hoped that Brittan's current visit will
help deepen mutual understanding, promote bilateral economic and
trade ties, and accelerate China's accession to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
EU stands so far as China's fourth largest trade partner with
bilateral trade volume reaching 39.7 billion US dollars last
year. The figure for the first eight months of this year amounted
to 25.31 billion US dollars, up 5.2 percent over the same period
of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, by the end of this June, EU member countries have
carried out 7,758 co-operative projects in China, with a total
commitment of 10.48 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
China's broad market and great developing potential will surely
provide EU with more co-operation opportunities in economy and
trade, Wu said, citing such sectors as new science and technology,
infrastructure construction, and sustainable development. In these
sectors, she said, EU could expand its investment and
technological transfer, and governments and administrative bodies
of both countries should render encouragement and support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Minister Urges Market Economy Recognization (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wu expressed her gratitude to Brittan and EU for their efforts
in talks concerning China's entry to the WTO, and her appreciation
over EU's independent position on this issue.
</P>
<P>
She hoped that EU would show more sincerity to produce
substantial progress in bilateral negotiations with a view to
reaching an early conclusion through joint efforts.
</P>
<P>
On the reduction of tariffs, Wu stressed that China has always
pursued an independent policy, and has made a big stride forward
in this regard.
</P>
<P>
According to her, China's general tariff rates have dropped
from 35 percent of 1995 to the present 17 percent, with a
reduction rate of over 60 percent. Moreover, China has committed
to cut the figure to the average level of that of the developing
countries by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the opening of China's service trade, Wu noted
that China has adopted a cautious attitude on this matter, and
believes opening of this sector can only be carried out step by
step instead of at a single move.
</P>
<P>
Wu mentioned EU's anti-dumping action against China, saying
this has aroused public concern and affected bilateral economic
and trade ties. It is learned that in the past two years, EU took
ten anti-dumping actions against China, bringing the number of its
registered anti-dumping cases to 69.
</P>
<P>
She suggested an anti-dumping consultative mechanism be
established under the China-Europe Mixed Committee so as to carry
out consultations and take preventive measures to avoid
confronting actions.
</P>
<P>
Regarding EU's unilateral quantitative limitation on China's
exports, Wu held that this is part of the EU's discriminative
trade policy against China. "China is the only sufferer of this
policy among all EU trade partners.
</P>
<P>
China opposes such discriminative trade policy, Wu said,
expressing the hope Brittan would work for an early cancellation
of such limitations and to remove obstacles for the long-term
development of bilateral economic and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
Brittan emphasized that on China's membership to the WTO, EU
will not impose its position on others, nor will it allow others
to force their views on itself. EU hopes China's early entry to
the WTO and will continue to work for this end together with the
Chinese side.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Wu and Brittan signed a memorandum of
understanding on co-operation and a financial agreement on three
co-operative projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
