<HEADLINE> Caspian Countries Urged to Prevent Harm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkmenistan President
Saparmurad Niyazov and Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Khzrazi
today urged the Caspian countries to prevent actions that are
harmful to the interests of each other.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency reported that in their meeting in
Ashkhabad, both Niyazov and Khzrazi stressed the need for settling
the status of the Caspian Sea through joint efforts of Caspian
countries.
</P>
<P>
The status of the Caspian and the building of oil pipelines
were the main topics of the two leaders. Khzrazi is on an official
visit to Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Niyazov also proposed that the two
countries establish a committee for exploring the mineral
resources of the Caspian.
</P>
<P>
Five countries border the Caspian Sea: the Russian Federation,
Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan, Azerbaijan and Iran. Because of disputes
among them over exploring its mineral resources, there is urgent
need for the countries to settle the sea's final status. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ministerial Panel at World Petroleum Congress (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Robert S. Kripowicz, deputy assistant secretary for fossil
energy of the U.S. Department of Energy, told the participants
that the oil and gas industry continues to be a crucial part of
the American economy. The oil and gas industry accounts for almost
5 percent of the country's gross output, or about 360 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S is the world's largest user of petroleum
and the world's largest importer, and depends on imports for 50
percent of its needs.
</P>
<P>
In the past three decades, the U.S. has established the
Strategic Petroleum Reserve (SPR) to safeguard the economy in case
of future oil supply disruptions, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Winston Dublin Green, who is in charge of Nigeria's oil
industry, said that his country is one of the ten largest oil
exporters in the world and will continue to play an important role
in the world's petroleum production and supply for the next 40
years.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Basic Industry of Cuba Marcos Portal Leon said that
Cuba has signed more than 40 economic association contracts with
foreign oil firms, including 22 production contracts for on-shore
and off-shore exploration with companies from Canada, Britain,
France, Sweden and Spain.
</P>
<P>
So far, Cuba has opened 13 oilfield blocks to foreign
investors, six on-shore and seven off-shore, ranging from 1,400 to
6,000 sq.m. in size. He said that Cuba wants to join the
international community quickly by absorbing advanced technology
from highly developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The participants said that technology and co-operation are a
key to sustained development in every country's petroleum industry
and that technical exchanges will increase in petroleum
exploration and in other areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
