<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Court Opens Hearing on Cairo Bus Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Amid tight security, two
Egyptians accused of killing nine German tourists and their
Egyptian driver in a deadly attack last month were put on trial at
a military court here today.
</P>
<P>
The two men, Saber Farahat Abu el-Ela and his brother Mahmoud,
had been caught red-handed at the scene of the appalling shooting
and petrol bomb attack on a tour bus in front of the renowned
Egyptian Museum in downtown Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Along with them in the trial before the Higher Military Court
were other seven men on charges of selling them weapons and
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
The first hearing was held at 11 a.m. today in a
heavily-guarded courtroom thronged with Arab and foreign reporters.
</P>
<P>
At the start of the session, the Farahat brothers asked the
court to assign a lawyer for their defense. They face charges of
manslaughter, arson, sabotage, illegal possession of weapons and
attack on police officers.
</P>
<P>
The mental status of Saber, who had been declared insane by a
Cairo court in a previous trial for murdering three foreigners in
a Cairo hotel in 1993, is yet to be determined by the military
court.
</P>
<P>
Citing that Saber was a madman who escaped from a lunatic
asylum just three days earlier, the Egyptian authorities
laboriously denied hints that Islamic extremists were behind the
attack as in the previous cases, in a bid to contain damages to
its multi-billion-dollar tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
After being overpowered by police, Saber claimed his attack was
to avenge blasphemous posters in Hebron that insulted Muslims.
</P>
<P>
The court ordered four of the defendants be medically examined
after their lawyers said that they have been tortured during
police interrogation.
</P>
<P>
The judge then ordered the court adjourned until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Farahat brothers were arrested by security police shortly
after they opened fire and threw petrol bombs into the bus of
German travelers at noon on September 18.
</P>
<P>
Cairo was quick to ban media coverage on the investigations of
the military court into the incident, which it said was different
from previous attacks carried out by the anti-government Islamic
militants.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,255 people have been killed since 1992 by
fundamentalist militants in a violent campaign against Egypt's
secular government.
</P>
<P>
The military prosecutor took over the case from the state
security on September 22, after President Hosni Mubarak ordered
the transfer for a speedy trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Remembers Helen Snow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A memorial service was held at
Beijing's Great Hall of the People today for Helen Foster Snow,
the noted American journalist, writer, and loyal friend of the
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Lei Jieqiong, vice-chairman of the National People's Congress
Standing Committee; and He Luli, vice-chairman of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference National Committee
attended the meeting, which was organized by the Chinese People's
Association for Friendship with Foreign Countries (CPAFFC) and the
Chinese Society for People's Friendship Studies (CSPFS).
</P>
<P>
Huang Hua, president of CSPFS, praised Helen Snow's unique and
outstanding contribution to friendship and understanding between
the Chinese and American peoples, saying that Helen, throughout
the long years of her life, best attested the friendship between
the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
In remembering Helen, it is imperative to emulate her spirit of
seeking truth from facts and to do fair and objective reporting,
and we must never forget her deep love for the people, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Qi Huaiyuan, the president of the CPAFFC said, Helen was one of
our earliest friends from other lands. While honoring the memory
of Helen Snow for her contribution to the cause of friendship
between the Chinese and American peoples, we also sincerely hope
that we shall have more and more friends, who, like Helen, will be
keenly interested in this cause and constantly work to consolidate
the bridge of friendship jointly built by the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the meeting were officials in charge of
relevant departments, friends from cultural and educational circle
and press, friends of the deceased and Helen's relatives and
friends living in US.  
</P>
</TEXT>
