<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Concerned About Vietnamese Refugees in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is very
concerned about Vietnamese refugees still remaining in Hong Kong,
Meng Xianying, head of a Chinese delegation, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Meng was speaking at the ongoing meeting of the executive
committee of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR). She thanked the UNHCR for its efforts in seeking a
solution to the problem of Vietnamese refugees in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
But she stressed that the Chinese government is "very much
concerned" that there are still about 2,100 Vietnamese refugees
after the conclusion in 1996 of the Comprehensive Plan of Action,
first agreed upon at the meeting of the International Conference
on Indo-Chinese Refugees here in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Meng said: "We hope that the parties concerned will take
further measures for the early repatriation of the remaining
Vietnamese refugees in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"We also hope that the relevant countries could adopt a more
positive and cooperative attitude in providing resettlement to the
remaining refugees in Hong Kong," she said.
</P>
<P>
Talking about China's role as an asylum country, Meng said
China has provided asylum for nearly 300,000 Indo-Chinese refugees
for almost 20 years despite its own limited resources. China had
persistently adhered to the principle of voluntary repatriation
and never repatriated refugees forcibly, she said.
</P>
<P>
"As for those refugees who wish to stay in China, we will help
them as ever. We hope that the international community and the
UNHCR will continue to support China's efforts in this regard,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Meng also expressed satisfaction over the relationship between
China and the UNHCR, which upgraded its branch office in China to
a regional office this year.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government would like to further strengthen its
cooperation with the UNHCR and join other countries in the efforts
to seek solutions to the refugee problems worldwide," she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
