<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two American Professors Share 1997 Nobel Economic Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 14 (Xinhua)--American Professor Robert
C. Merton and Professor Myron S. Scholes won 1997 Nobel Prize in
Economics today "for a new method to determine the value of
derivatives."
</P>
<P>
The Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences announced here that these
two professors, together with the late Fischer Black, "developed a
pioneering formula for the valuation of stock options."
</P>
<P>
"Their methodology has paved the way for economic valuations in
many areas. It has also generated new types of financial
instruments and facilitated more efficient risk management in
society," the Academy said.
</P>
<P>
In a modern market economy, it is essential for firms and
householders to select an appropriate level of risk in their
transactions. However, it is a prerequisite for them to adopt
scientific instruments for efficient management of the risk.
</P>
<P>
"A new method to determine the value of derivatives stands out
among the foremost contributions to economic sciences over the
last 25 years," said the Academy.
</P>
<P>
Robert Merton, born in 1944 and now professor of economics at
Harvard University, and Myron Scholes, born in 1941 and professor
of finance at Stanford University, developed the new method of
option valuation in close collaboration with Fischer Black, who
died in his fifties in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In 1973, Black and Scholes published what has come to be known
as the Black-Scholes Formula, which thousands of traders and
investors now use every day to value stock options in markets
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Besides the valuation method, Merton and Scholes have made
several significant contributions to financial economics.
</P>
<P>
The Nobel Prize in Economics was instituted in 1968 by the Bank
of Sweden in memory of the Swedish dynamite inventor Alfred
Nobel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
