<HEADLINE> Iran, Turkmenistan to Form Oil Consortium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Turkmenistan have
decided to form an oil consortium for oil and gas development in
the Caspian Sea, Iran's official news agency IRNA reported today.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi and his Turkmen
counterpart Boris Shikhmuradov made the announcement at a joint
press conference held in Ashkhabad, capital of Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi arrived in Ashkhabad Monday on an official visit as
part of Iran's efforts to enhance its relations with Central Asian
Republics.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi was quoted as saying that Turkmenistan has excluded
three out of 11 oil blocks in the Caspian Sea put on an
international tender, pending the determination of their legal
status.
</P>
<P>
"The three excluded blocks are located between Iranian and
Turkmen territorial waters," Kharrazi said.
</P>
<P>
On joint venture projects to be implemented by Iran and
Turkmenistan in the oil and gas sector, Kharrazi said that a
memorandum of understanding has been reached between the two
countries for laying pipelines across Iran to pump Turkmen gas to
Turkey and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Oil ministers of Iran, Turkey and Turkmenistan would meet in
November to discuss related issues.
</P>
<P>
As for the legal status of the Caspian Sea, Shikhmuradov said
that during their recent talks Iranian and Turkmen officials
agreed to adopt a joint stance.
</P>
<P>
He said the issue was brought up and discussed at a meeting
between Kharrazi and Turkmen President Saparmurad Niyazov
Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
