<HEADLINE> Teenager Chen Completes Gold Double at National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Chen Yan, who broke the world
record in the 400m individual medley yesterday, completed her gold
double by taking the women's 200m freestyle at the National Games
here Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Chen of Liaoning province clocked her career and the year-best
of one minute 57.30 seconds, two hundredths of a second ahead of
local star Wang Luna. The bronze medal went to Olympian Shan Ying
of Chinese Army in 1:59.43.
</P>
<P>
"I was very tired in the last 50 meters," Chen said. "But I
managed to hold on for the gold. I have four other events in the
Games, and I will continue to try my best."
</P>
<P>
"Chen's timing is the best in the past two years," said Zhou
Ming, vice head coach of the Chinese national swimming team. "Wang
also has the calibre to win the gold. She staged fierce challenge
in the last 50 meters."
</P>
<P>
Local teenager Wang Wei overcame a cold to capture the gold in
the women's 100m breaststroke in an Asian mark of one minute and
8.26 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Teammate Zhang Yi finished second in 1:08.61 and Yuan Yuan of
the Chinese Army was third in 1:09.60.
</P>
<P>
Han Xue of Beijing, who holds the 50m breaststroke short-course
world record, came in a modest seventh place.
</P>
<P>
"The 100m event is not my favorite," Said Wang. "The gold and
the time are beyong my expectation. Only three days ago, I caught
a fever with a tempreture of 40-degree centigrade."
</P>
<P>
Chen's coach Han Jiayan failed to show up after the competition
due to illness. In his place, Zhang Yanmou who pinned high hopes
upon the 16-year-old, said that "Chen was an inborn swimmer with
1.78 meters in height at the age of 16. Hardworking and talented
as she is, the girl is sure to catch the limelight in her next
four events."
</P>
<P>
In the men's 400m individual medley, Xiong Guoming, who won six
gold medals in the last National Games four years ago, retained
his title with an Asain mark of four minutes and 19.03 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Jin Hao of Shangdong province finished second in 4:23.13 and
Wang Wei of Shanghai came third 0.22 seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
Xiong and Wang also claimed the gold in the 4X200m freestyle
relay for Shanghai along with Ye Liangchen and Chen Zhou, the gold
medalist in the 200m freestyle on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Coach Zhou said the swimming competitions in the National Games
reached a very high level.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very glad that the swimmers, especially the youngsters,
achieved such good results," Zhou said. "But do not be astonished
at it. After two years in low tones for the Chinese swimmers,
it's the right time for the new bloods to emerge as the stars."
</P>
<P>
Zhou said the Chinese swimmers are expected to achieve good
timings and even world records in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
Should they keep training hard and steeling their nerves at
home and abroad, the new stars are sure to make the splashes in
the World Swimming Championships next January in Perth, Australia,
the coach said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
