<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli President, PM Meet to Soothe Differences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer
Weizman met today with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu amid
reports about their differences over resuming the peace talks
with Syria.
</P>
<P>
The two met for only 19 minutes at the Presidential residence
in western Jerusalem. Both the President's Office and the Prime
Minister's Office described the meeting as a "good one."
</P>
<P>
Weizman reportedly briefed Netanyahu on his talks last week
with United States President Bill Clinton in Washington, which
focused on ways to push forward the Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks and resume the stalled peace talks with Syria.
</P>
<P>
The president said he asked Clinton to invite both Netanyahu
and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat
to visit Washington in order to advance the peace process, that
has just been restored following a seven-month freeze. He said
Clinton had accepted his request, but he did not elaborate when
Netanyahu and Arafat would be invited.
</P>
<P>
Weizman repeated his denial that he hinted in his meeting
with Clinton that Netanyahu was ready to give up the
occupied Golan Heights in order to resume the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The reported Weizman's remarks on Golan concession created an
uproar between the President's Office, the Foreign Ministry and
the Prime Minister's Office. Weizman charged Israeli Ambassador
to the U.S, Eliyahu Ben-Elissar for leaking his remarks to the
media, denying that he had ever talked about the Golan issue.
</P>
<P>
Despite being the ceremonial head of state, Weizman has
been outspoken about politics, especially on the government's
policies on the peace process. He is often at odds with
Netanyahu over controversial remarks he made to foreign guests
that revealed their differences over the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace process has been suspended since early
last year following a wave of suicide bombings launched Islamic
militants and the access to power in May last year by the
hardline Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
Israel has repeatedly called for unconditional resumption of
peace talks, but Syria insists that the talks should be restarted
from the point where they were left off last year with the
previous Labor government, namely on Israeli promise to fully
withdraw troops from the strategic Golan Heights taken by Israel
in the 1967 War.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged deadlock in the peace track has led to fears about
possible armed confrontation between the two sides, and Israel
believes that Damascus is preparing for a military attack aimed at
forcing Israel to resume the peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
