<HEADLINE> Chinese Visit South Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Some 2,000 Chinese scientists
have been to the South Pole in the past 13 years, according to the
National Bureau of Oceanography.
</P>
<P>
Many went to the site following the instructions of late Deng
Xiaoping in 1984: "Make a contribution to mankind's peaceful
utilization of the South Pole."
</P>
<P>
China has sent 13 teams to explore the ice-covered continent
and built two stations there, according to officials attending a
meeting here today to mark the 13th anniversary of Deng's
instructions.
</P>
<P>
The bureau has a key scientific program to study the far-off
land and its biology, geography, and atmosphere. 
</P>
