<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Rural Women Key to Food Security and </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- October 15 is named by the
United Nations as "World Rural Women's Day". Starting from 1996,
the day has been observed one day before "World Food Day" to
increase awareness of the need to focus on rural women as a key
to food security and sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
There is no doubt that rural women who comprise more than one
quarter of the world's total population, is a vital force in food
production and rural development.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that women produce 60 to 80 percent of basic
foodstuffs in sub-Saharan Africa, process 100 percent of basic
household foodstuffs and meet 90 percent of household water and
fuel needs throughout Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, rural women are easily neglected in this regard, not
to mention many small-scale food producers and subsistence
farmers living in food-deficit countries where their potential
contribution to improve food security and vital contribution to
society are largely unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, most rural women live in poverty and lack basic
education and training from one generation to the next. They also
lack technologies and credit or equal rights to land tenure and
inheritance.
</P>
<P>
African women receive less than one percent of the total
credit available to agriculture. They often suffer from anaemia
and general poor nutrition and health. An estimated 1.3 billion
people live in extreme poverty of less than one US dollar a day,
most of whom are women and children living in the least developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the International Fund for Agricultural
Development, the number of rural women living in absolute poverty
had increased by 50 percent over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
It is noteworthy that development of rural women is not only
related to the food security and rural development, but also to
the eradication of poverty in the world.
</P>
<P>
To promote the development of rural women, experts suggest
that first, they must be provided with opportunity to receive
education and training and let them learn modern technologies and
reduce the tremendous daily workload in their households and on
farms. Secondly, governments must provide inputs and credits to
support their agricultural production. Thirdly, better access to
markets will be offered to enable them to derive more income from
their labour.
</P>
<P>
Through the observation of "World Rural Women's Day", the
United Nations has called on governments all over the world to
ensure rural development is given higher priority and that more
national income reaches the rural poor.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that if rural women's role is fully recognized,
it will certainly promote the food security and sustainable
development in the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Date Set To China's Yangtze River For Dam Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China's State Council today
approved a plan to block the Yangtze River, China's longest, on
November 8 for the giant Three Gorges Dam project.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at the 63rd meeting of the State Council
Executive Committee, following a report by Guo Shuyan,
Vice-Chairman of the State Council Three Gorges Project
Construction Committee on work in progress.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng chaired Monday's meeting of the committee in
Beijing to discuss a report on preparations. Li said the project
has gone smoothly for the past five years and the design for
blocking the river is feasible and the resettlement of local
people has gone well.
</P>
<P>
Li said these attest to the correctness of the central
government's policies and principles on the Three Gorges project,
and the adoption of international practices like the legal-person
system, the bidding system, project supervision, and investment
management have had positive results, and the cost has stayed
within the budget.
</P>
<P>
He said the blocking is an important part of the Three Gorges
Project as the end of the first phase and start of the second, and
that there should be good preparation to reach the goal.
</P>
<P>
The dikes in the second phase should be built as quickly as
possible in order to ensure safety during the flood season in
1998, he said, and attention should be paid to installation of the
turbo-generators and to completing the power transmission and
transformation project and supportive projects, to see that they
will go into operation with the opening of the permanent shiplock
by 2003.
</P>
<P>
Li also spoke on the resettlement project, ecological and
environmental protection, agricultural development, and protection
of cultural relics in the project area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
