<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Future Business Leaders of Asia Must Be Far-sighted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Asia needs far-sighted young
business leaders to meet the challenge of the information age of
the next century, a Singaporean entrepreneur said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a plenary session in parallel of the 1997 East Asia
Economic Summit, Ho Kwon-Ping, chairman of Wah-Chang International
of Singapore, said that the young generation of business leaders
should heed the wind change rather than scramble when typhoon
arrives.
</P>
<P>
He believed the young generation of business leaders can create
a better and stronger Asia. However, this is not a second "Asian
miracle" but a vision which can be achieved through idealism and
hard work, he said.
</P>
<P>
Yoshimasa Hayashi, member of the House of Councilors of Japan,
said that the difference between the industrial age and the
informational age lies in the change from a free global market
promoting free trade for products to a free global network
promoting communications and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
A cooperative culture for global cooperation should be
developed in the next century so as to coordinate the values of
the Western and Eastern countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
The next generation of business leaders in Asia should adopt a
new way of thinking and a new way of management, said Tian Wei,
managing director of Hong Kong's China Civil Engineering
Construction Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Tian stressed the importance of localizing the cooperation in
order to explore business opportunities. That means more
compromises than confrontations, he added.
</P>
<P>
Every country has different standard of value and different
economic and social background and overseas investors should try
to gain local support, he said, adding that foreign investors are
hard to work in Asia without local support.
</P>
<P>
Kim Sung Joo from South Korea, the only businesswoman to speak
at the session, said that Asian women should play a more important
role in the next century.
</P>
<P>
She urged Asian businessmen to pay close attention to the role
of highly educated women and promote specialized training for
women through updated techniques. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serb Leaders Committed to Solving Political Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 13 (Xinhua) - - Bosnia's Serb President,
Biljana Plavsic, and Serb member of the Bosnian presidency Momcilo
Krajisnik have reiterated commitment to their recent agreement
aimed at resolving the political crisis in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Meeting today with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, who
mediated in the agreement on September 24, the two leaders said
the agreement is of great importance in solving the problems in
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, Plavsic and Krajisnik agreed to take all
necessary steps to stop any conflicts that would threaten the
unity of Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to hold elections for the republic's
parliament on November 15, and for the presidency and the Serb
member of the three-man Bosnian presidency on December 17.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, the two leaders adopted the suggestion from
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) to
defer the parliamentary election to November 23.
</P>
<P>
The present political crisis within the Bosnian Serb leadership
began in early July, when Plavsic dissolved the parliament despite
strong opposition from its members.
</P>
<P>
Then Plavsic's exposure of high-level corruption led to further
conflict with Bosnian Serb hard-liners who expelled her from the
Serb Social Democratic Party and demanded her resignation as
president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Urges Quicker Localization in Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese official in charge of
Hong Kong and Macao affairs said here today that the localization
of civil servants, law and the use of Chinese as an official
language should be quickened for a smooth handover of power.
</P>
<P>
Chen Ziying, deputy director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs
 Office of the State Council of China, urged the Macao government
in a speech today to "truly take the responsibility" for resolving
 the three major issues that are vital to the smooth transition
and handover of power in Macao.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Macao government has taken some measures, and
the localization process has made progress. But, he pointed out,
the progress has lagged behind the schedule for a smooth handover
of power in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"It is an urgent task to solve the three major issues," he
stressed. "The localization of senior and middle ranking
officials, in particular, should achieve a breakthrough this year
and next. A favorable condition should also be created so that
leading posts of the SAR government will be held by Chinese
citizens from among Macao's permanent residents."
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, the Chinese language should be used more
widely so that it will enjoy the same official language status as
the Portuguese in such spheres as administration, legislation and
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
As to the localization of laws, he said, the civil law, the law
of civil procedure, the commercial law and some other important
laws should be localized as soon as possible, thus establishing a
set of laws that are in conformity with the Macao Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
More law professionals who are needed by the Macao SAR should
also be trained, he added.
</P>
<P>
Chen arrived here on Monday for a five-day visit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
