<HEADLINE> 2 Israeli Soldiers Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese guerrillas wounded two
Israeli soldiers in an attack in south Lebanon today, Lebanese
Orient Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Iranian Hezbollah said today its fighters fired rockets
and machine guns at several military outposts of Israeli troops
and South Lebanon militia allies in the Israeli-occupied enclave.
</P>
<P>
In a response to the attack, two Israeli warplanes blasted at
1:30 pm (GMT 11:30) the village of Jenta in the country's northern
province of Baalbek, where Hezbollah's headquarters are believed
located.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, no further detail of casualties was reported for the
Israeli attack, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese Hezbollah, or Party of God, is leading a guerrilla
war to oust Israeli troops and their local militia allies from the
1,100-square-kilometer "security zone," which was set up by Israel
in 1985 to prevent cross-border attacks. 
</P>
