<HEADLINE> More World Records Broken in Women's 59-kg Weightlifting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Chen Yanqing of Jiangsu
province claimed the women's 59-kg category weightlifting title in
world records at the Eighth National Games here Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old strongwoman lifted 112.5 kgs in snatch and
137.5 kgs in jerk for a combined total of 250 kgs, all surpassing
the listed world records.
</P>
<P>
The previous snatch record of 100 kgs was set by Zhou Fei'e in
the second East Asian Games in May 1997, the jerk mark of 125 kgs
was set on Monday by Thailand's Suta Khassaraporn in the South
East Asian Games in Indonesia, while the two-lift total record of
220 kgs was set by Chinese Chen Xiaomin in the Asian Games in
Hiroshima in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Song Zhijuan, a 17-year-old strongwoman in the Liberation Army,
snatched up 115 kgs to break the Chinese national record of 110.5
kgs set by Chen Xiaomin in the National Championships last year.
</P>
<P>
However, Song failed in her three attempts on 135 kgs in the
jerk event, bowing out of the contention for the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
All the top four finishers bettered the three listed world
marks in the National Games.
</P>
<P>
In the morning, Yang Xia broke the world records to take the
women's 54-kg title after the Chinese strongwomen broke all the
world records in the 46-kg and 50-kg classes on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
