<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani Official to Visit Germany, U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Ahsan Iqbal, chief
coordinator of Pakistan's 2010 Program, a socio-economic
development program, will leave here Wednesday for Berlin,
Germany, to attend a two-day seminar to celebrate the Golden
Jubilee of Pakistan's independence.
</P>
<P>
Iqbal told the press today that he would present a paper of the
2010 Program at the seminar, which is organized by the Institute
of Industrial Economy, Germany, and will be attended by German
economists and Pakistani intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
He said the program was designed "to respond to the global
challenge and to allow us to leap forward and catch up with the
Asian nations that have done so well."
</P>
<P>
The program is catching the attention of the international
media and global economic circles, said Iqbal, adding it would
help the rest of the world to know how Pakistanis visualize the
next century.
</P>
<P>
The main goals of the program are investment in the country's
infrastructure, promotion of human resources including education
and health care, and creation of new industries, according to
Iqbal.
</P>
<P>
The paper of the program quoted Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif as saying that "we want to double the per capita income to
1,000 U.S. dollars and to make sure no child is without schooling.
 We want universal health care, clean water and sanitation."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan needs to give the country a social-economic
foundation, Iqbal said.
</P>
<P>
From Berlin, Iqbal said he would leave for the United States to
attend a similar seminar in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
He will also have meetings with the Pakistani community in the
U.S. to discuss with them their role and responsibilities in the
development of Pakistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
