<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Chief Says Olympics Needs Commercialization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Juan Antonio Samaranch,
President of the International Olympic Committee (IOC), said here
Tuesday that commercialization was an indispensable part of the
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
"We need commercialization in sports. We need commercialization
in Olympic Games," said Samaranch, who was invited by the Chinese
Olympic Committee for visiting the Eighth National Games.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the IOC chief warned that "we must be aware that Olympic
Games must be run by sports officials, not by commercials."
</P>
<P>
For this reason, he said, the Olympic Games is the only sports
meet in the world that has no advertising boards inside the
competition venues.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch, who cut the ribbon for the Chinese Fourth Sports
Arts Exhibition on Monday, said sports culture is very important
in the Olympic Movement.
</P>
<P>
"We have said many times that the Olympic Movement is not only
dealing with sports, but also dealing with culture and arts," he
told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He added that golfers are unlikely to take part in the Olympic
Games before 2008 though he vowed to open the Olympic door
thoroughly to the professional athletes.
</P>
<P>
"We want to have all the best athletes in if they respect the
Olympic Charter," he said. "We're talking with international golf
organizations but golf will not be in the Games before 2008."
</P>
<P>
The president also appreciated China's efforts in sports
development.
</P>
<P>
"We are very interested in the People's Republic of China's
efforts to promote high-level sports competition and at the same
time promote sports education for the people," he added.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch praised the opening ceremony of the Chinese Eighth
National Games as one of the best he'd seen in his life. "It was
at an Olympic level," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said China should apply again for hosting the Olympic Games.
"Today, I'm sure, as President of IOC, that China has the ability
to present an excellent Games to the world."
</P>
<P>
On the doping issue, the IOC chief said the International
Amateur Athletic Federation ruled right to reduce from four to two
years against those cheaters, saying "it was a good decision. The
punishment must be the same in all internaitonal federations. I
think two years is enough." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
