<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's First Private Power Company Formed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has formed its first
private power company to build and operate a 108 megawatt (MW)
power barge in the country's southwest region, a local newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newly-formed company, Khulna Power Company Ltd. (KPCL), is
composed of Wartsila NSD Power Development Ltd., a U.S.-based
independent power developer, and its two Bangladeshi partners,
the Financial Express said.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture company will invest about 100 million U.S.
dollars for putting in place a barge-mounted power plant on a
fast-track basis by mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement to be signed soon, Wartsila will have a 75
percent stake in the company while the two local investors will
each have a 12.50 percent share in the company.
</P>
<P>
Of the total 100-million-dollar investment, the company expects
to raise nearly 70 million dollars from different international
financial agencies and the remaining 30 million dollars will come
as equity from the co-investors.
</P>
<P>
The KPCL power barge will be located at Goalpara near Khulna
town 140 kilometers from Dhaka, and the plant is expected to go
into operation eight months after the signing of necessary
agreements with the authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
