<HEADLINE> Airbus Group to Become Corporation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The four-nation European Airbus
Industries consortium today formally announced that it will
streamline its structure by becoming a corporation with one single
management, at the beginning of 1999.
</P>
<P>
An Airbus single corporate entity would be formed on the basis
of the current structure consisting of Aerospatiale SNI of France,
British Aerospace PLC, Construcciones Aeronauticas SA of Spain and
Daimler-Benz Aerospace AG of Germany, the companies said in a
joint press release.
</P>
<P>
The four partners had agreed to integrate all activities needed
to define, develop and produce the present and future Airbus
product line under the responsibility of one management, the press
release said.
</P>
<P>
The integration has been seen as an effort to counterweigh the
merger of the Boeing Company and McDonnell Douglas of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Edzard Reuter, current chairman the Airbus supervisory board,
has announced that he would step down at the beginning of 1998 at
the latest to enable Airbus parters to nominate a new president
for the integrated management, and a new chairman for the
supervisory board.
</P>
<P>
One of the presidents of the four Airbus partners would be
elected as future chairman of the supervisory board, the companies
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
