<HEADLINE> Four Former East German Coaches Sent to Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Four former East German swimming
coaches were sent to trial Tuesday with giving banned anabolic
drugs to minors without telling either them or their parents,
according to prosecutors here.
</P>
<P>
Dieter Lindemann, who coached world and Olympic champion
Franziska van Almsick until last year, Volker Frischke, Rolf
Glaser and Dieter Krause, who all coached at the Dynamo Berlin
club were sent for trial.
</P>
<P>
The quartet were alleged to have administered drugs to teenage
swimmers from 1974 to 1989 with the agreement of the East German
sporting authorities.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday Joerg Hoffmann, who won the 400 and 1,500 meters
freestyle world titles for the newly-unified Germany in 1991 in
Perth, was quoted as saying that he was given pills containing the
banned anabolic Oral-Turinabol in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Hoffmann said on Monday that he did not know at the time what
the pills were and added he would probably not enter the world
championships next January in Perth, Australia.
</P>
<P>
Another former world record holder, Karen Koenig, said last
week popping pills was part of everyday life for swimmers in East
Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
