<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long-Term Unemployment Increases In Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Official figures today
revealed that more than one in three jobless Australians were
stuck on the long-term unemployment queue in September, sparking
opposition calls for the federal government to halt skilled
immigration.
</P>
<P>
The is the biggest monthly rise in long-term jobless numbers in
four and a half years, despite unemployment improving last month
to 8.6 percent from 8.7 percent the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics said the number of people
who are jobless for 12 months or more rose to 264,900 in September
from 247,800 the previous month. More than half of these had been
out of work for at least two years, according to the statistics.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said long-term unemployment as a proportion of total
unemployment rose to 33.5 percent in September from 31 percent in
August.
</P>
<P>
Federal Employment Minister David Kemp said the coalition's
employment service reforms would help cut long-term unemployment.
But he refused to put a date on when the figures were likely to
fall.
</P>
<P>
"The government is putting into place a major reform to assist
long-term unemployed people, with the contracting out of the
employment service office," he told reporters here today.
</P>
<P>
Opposition employment spokesman Martin Ferguson said the
long-term jobless queue had risen by 58,800 since the coalition
government cut Labor's Working Nation program in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson today met with West Australian nurses concerned about
federal and state government plans to bring in foreign nurses to
fill a shortage.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian government's got to say to employers 'No, we
are not prepared to let you resort to the easy option of bringing
workers in from overseas, we have got worsening unemployment in
Australia,'" he said.
</P>
<P>
"We should adopt job policies which give local people the
skills, the training or the re-training," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
