<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The joint Jordanian-Syrian Yarmuk River Committee
ended two days of meeting here today by agreeing to go ahead with
plans to construct Al Wahdeh (unity) Dam on the river to provide
the two countries with irrigation and drinking water,
semi-official Jordan Times reported.
</P>
<P>
It would take up some 400 million U.S. dollars to complete the
project, which will totally be built on Syrian territory, said
Dureid Mahasneh, the secretary-general of the Jordan Valley
Authority.
</P>
<P>
After the dam was constructed, Jordan would get 85 million
cubic meters of water annually from the river, according to
Mahasneh.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed in 1987 to build the dam but it was
postponed due to the developments in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Yarmuk River mainly crosses the border of Israel and
Syria and spreads branches into the territory of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- German is to provide Jordan with technical assistance
worth nearly 6 million German Marks (about 3.2 million
U.S. dollars) to finance the country's development projects,
according to four memoranda signed here Monday, semi-official
Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The memoranda were signed by Jordanian Minister of Planning
Rima Khalaf and German Ambassador to Jordan Peter Mende.
</P>
<P>
German has been extending help to the kingdom in recent years
by providing grants and aid.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan has said that political tension in the Middle
East soured a favorable outlook for its tourism industry for 1997.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's policies caused
tension in the region, which scared off some visitors and upset
healthy growth forecasts for Jordan's tourism in 1997, Tourism
Minister Akel Beltaji told reporters Monday.
</P>
<P>
"If the situation in Israel was what it had been in 1994 and
1995, this year 1997 we would have reached double-digit growth,"
Beltaji said.
</P>
<P>
Now Jordan forecasts for 1997 a modest 2 to 5 percent rise
from last year's 1.13 million tourist arrivals.
</P>
<P>
Jordan managed to maintain at least modest growth this year
by marketing itself as a sole destination rather than part of a
wider Middle East tour, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Tourism has been the pillar industry for the kingdom, making
up respectively 37 percent of its foreign currency income and 11
percent of its gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT, October (Xinhua) -- A three-day conference, organized
by Lebanese central bank and the banks association, urged
bankers to extend loans to small businesses, Lebanese
English-language newspaper the Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speakers from international banks, including representatives
from Egypt, the United States and Germany, highlighted the
potential for lending to small businesses.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the conference, which opened Monday, said that
in other parts of the world, small business loans are mostly
extended by banks.
</P>
<P>
In Lebanon, however, the majority of the estimated 3 million
U.S. dollars of small loans is provided by non-governmental
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The paper said banks in Lebanon have been reluctant to lend to
small enterprises because the banks are used to dealing with
established businesses, and lending on collateral basis.
</P>
<P>
Judith Brandsma, a World Bank specialist, said Lebanese banks
would have to toughen up their collection procedures when
dealing with small businesses.
</P>
<P>
"Banks have to be tough and serious, knocking on the
shoulders of borrowers if they are one day late," she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
