<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Launches Rural Travel and Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is launching a rural
travel and transport program (RTTP) to improve its road network
throughout the country for sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
Officiating a workshop to launch the RTTP here today, Bennie
Mwinga, minister of local government and housing told the
participants that the poor infrastructure and deterioratig
situation of Zambia's road network, due to overloading and
insufficient funds for rehabilitation and regular maintenance,
have hampered the country's economic development and people's
daily life.
</P>
<P>
The RTTP, with the assistance of the World Bank and
coordination by the ministry of local government and housing,
aims at promoting the "immediate means of transport" in the
country. It will run a two-year period starting from 1998 and is
supported by the governments of Denmark, Norway, Sweden and
Switzerland, said a pamphlet released at the workshop.
</P>
<P>
The RTTP is a component of the sub-Saharan Africa transport
policy program (SSATP), which is a collaborative effort between
many bilateral and multilateral organizations to assist
governments to formulate and implement improved transport
policies in the region.
</P>
<P>
During his speech, Mwinga said in order to promote the travel
and transport system in the rural areas, his ministry is
addressing the "rural isolation" by formulating and putting in
place a coherent policy framework and institutional focus for the
planning, funding and maintenance of rural roads.
</P>
<P>
All the stakeholders and targeted beneficiaries are supposed
to share responsibilities within clearly defined roles and the
RTTP related costs in order to make the programs sustainable, the
minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the funds to be given will be put to "good
use", Mwinga called on donor countries and organizations to
provide the "much needed financial support" to the RTTP by
adequately directing the "much desired funds" to the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
"Without donor support," said Mwinga, "it will be extremely
difficult for us to implement this well intentioned program."
</P>
<P>
The workshop, which will end on Thursday attracted more than
100 people, including the resident representative of the World
Bank, many senior government officials as well as road experts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
