<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Giant Water Projects Kicked off in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today gave the go-ahead to implement three new water and sewerage
ventures with a total cost of 1.3 billion Egyptian pounds (382.3
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
While inaugurating a housing and construction exhibition fair
on prospects of construction held at Cairo International
Conference Center, Mubarak gave the green light for the projects
through closed television circuits linked to the construction
sites.
</P>
<P>
The first project involves a sanitary drainage plant in Port
Said, the second transfers Nile water to the Red Sea resort of
Hurghada for the first time through a pipeline and the third
implicates operating untreated water pipeline from the Suez Canal
city of Qantara to Port Said.
</P>
<P>
The first project, which was build in cooperation with the
United States Agency for International Development, is among the
world's largest with a treatment capacity of 3 million cubic
meters of sewerage water per day.
</P>
<P>
The fair, entitled "Prospects of Construction", shed light on
the government's achievements and plans to provide further
potable water and sewerage networks at the national level.
</P>
<P>
Since Mubarak took office in 1981, the government has been
investing over 11 billion pounds (3.2 billion dollars) in 138 new
drinking water projects, according to Minister of Housing and
Utilities Mohamed Ibrahim Soliman.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing achievements in the past 16 years, he said the
sewerage projects in Egypt increased from only nine in 1952 to 26
in 1981, to 125 in 1997 and are expected to reach 568 in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Drinking water projects, he added, standing at 52 before 1952,
rose to 173 in 1981 and shot to 1,083 today. The target is 1,389
drinking water projects by the year 2017. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record High Number of Crimes Reported in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The number of crimes reported in
Japan set a postwar record of some 2.46 million in 1996, up 30,000
from the previous year, said the Justice Ministry today.
</P>
<P>
Of the total criminal cases last year, 654,000 were related to
traffic violations, said the ministry's 1997 white paper on crime.
</P>
<P>
And of the 78 percent increase over 50 years ago, when some
1,387,000 criminal cases were reported, 60 percent was related to
road incidents.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, a total of 979,000 suspects were arrested on criminal
charges, up 9,000 from the year before.
</P>
<P>
Theft topped the list of reported crimes at 64.4 percent,
followed by traffic-related crimes at 26.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Among those convicted for criminal offenses, 49.2 percent were
under 20 years old, an increase from the 30 percent level reported
every year up until 1977.
</P>
<P>
However, the figure was lower than in 1989, when it reached a
record high at 57.4 percent, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Marginally Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Australian dollar ended
marginally weaker today as the jobs data had prompted the market
to revise its rate cut expectations, and many market participants
now think the Reserve Bank of Australia is more likely to leave
rates on hold for the time being.
</P>
<P>
The Australian currency ended at 73.78 US cents, down from
73.82, and off an intraday high of 74.15.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar rode higher on the back of a surge in the
New Zealand dollar exchange rate against the US dollar before
options- related selling saw it grind steadily lower.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand dollar rose to an intraday high of 65.19 US
cents before it closed at 64.82, up from 64.66 previously.
</P>
<P>
"Since it hit the highs, the Aussie has seen steady selling,"
said a trader. "There is good options-related selling up around
that 74.10-15 area."
</P>
<P>
Traders also said the Australian dollar continued to be
supported by a more positive economic outlook and should be able
to sustain most of the gains made last week.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank of Australia global trading manager foreign
exchange Rick Lloyd said the market is no longer expecting the
Reserve Bank of Australia to cut interest rates in the short term.
</P>
<P>
Last week's strong September labor force figures effectively
capsized previous high expectations in the market that the Reserve
Bank of Australia would move to ease monetary policy in the short
term.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended at 89.53 yen, compared to 89.16,
and at 1.2926 marks, from 1.2964 previously.  
</P>
</TEXT>
