<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore PM Optimistic About Southeast Asia Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister of Singapore
Goh Chok Tong today expressed his optimism about the Southeast
Asian economies, saying countries affected by the recent financial
turbulence in the region will be able to recover fairly quickly.
</P>
<P>
In a keynote speech at the 1997 East Asia Economic Summit being
held here, Goh argued that the current financial turmoil
represents only a temporary, though painful, setback to the onward
march of Southeast Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
"Just as the haze which blankets the region will clear, the
miasma of uncertainty which has affected sentiment in Asia will
after a while evaporate," he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that while near-term growth in East
Asia will likely slow down, the economies in the region will not
stall because of good economic fundamentals. Most East Asian
economies run fiscal surpluses, have high saving and investment
rates and have some of the highest ratios of trade to GDP in the
world.
</P>
<P>
"Growth in foreign direct investment in the region will
continue," he said, stressing that the recent currency devaluation
in the region is unlikely to have a lasting impact on foreign direct
investment flows.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said East Asian economies have benefited
from economic globalization and financial liberalization. Although
the relaxation of capital controls by the East Asian economies has
made them vulnerable to the vicissitudes of the global market, the
governments need to liberalize their economies further rather than
to restrict the flow of trade in goods and service.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that Singapore will continue to invest heavily in
the economies of its neighbors and East Asia as a whole because it
has faith in the growth prospects of the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
