<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Tumble Below 17,000 Level, Then Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the stock market
here tumbled below the 17,000 line for the first time in two years
but rebounded on bargain hunting in blue chips to close the day.
</P>
<P>
During the morning session today, the key Nikkei average of 225
selected issues on the First Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange
briefly fell below the 17,000 line for the first time in two years.
</P>
<P>
The index was the lowest since August 15, 1995, when the
average dipped as low as 16,869.15.
</P>
<P>
Traders were quoted by Japanese media reports as saying that
market participants moved to sell because of disappointment at the
government's proposed measures to stimulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
However, the Nikkei average rebounded to gain 101.69 points, or
0.59 percent, from the previous day's close to end at 17,306,39.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX),
covering all issues on the First Section, edged down 0.57 points,
or 0.04 percent, to 1,337.90.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section came to an estimated 400 million
shares, up from Monday's 328.02 million shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
