<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Poverty Eases in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Based on income measure, the
proportion of Bangladeshis living in poverty in rural areas fell
from 57.5 percent in 1987 to 51.7 percent in 1994, a local
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed in a recent report of an ongoing study on
rural poverty at the Bangladesh Institute of Development Studies,
The New Nation said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, while 39 percent of rural households
saw improvement in their economic conditions, 17 percent saw
deterioration, and 44 percent said there had been no changes.
</P>
<P>
An important factor behind the improved rural economic
conditions has been the drastic fall in the growth of rural
population due to rapid rural-urban migration and a drop in the
natural growth of population, the report pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The report added that migration from rural areas to cities
reduced rural population by nearly 1 percent per year during
1987-94.
</P>
<P>
Another factor is that over 80 percent of rural males and
around 70 percent of rural females now have access to emergency
credits, mostly soft loans, the report stated.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh, one of the poorest countries in the world, is now
implementing a poverty alleviation program with the assistance
from the World Bank and other donor institutions and countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
