<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Gas Export to Grow 20-Fold in 15 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Middle East region's gas
exports will most probably increase by about 20 folds in the 15
years to 2010, international researchers forecast here today.
</P>
<P>
Middle East is expected to sell around 140 billion cubic metres
of gas overseas a year by 2010, compared to 6.8 billion cubic
metres in 1995, according to forecasts by researchers from the
Iranian Petroleum Institute and National Iranian Oil Company.
</P>
<P>
The researchers presented their results to the ongoing 15th World
Petroleum Congress here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
According to their paper, Middle East gas production and marketed
consumption have shown remarkable vigour in the past decade, but are
still "anaemic when compared with the region's formidable gas
reserves".
</P>
<P>
Of the world's two major natural gas provinces, the largest one,
namely Russia, is being exploited, while the other, the Middle East,
is rather untapped, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that Russia accounts for 34.4 percent of the world's
total proved gas reserves and the Middle East 32.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Russia produced 26.6 percent of the world's total gas
output while the Middle East made up only 6.6 percent of worldwide
production.
</P>
<P>
According to researchers, the Middle East countries have worked
out plans to increase their gas production and a number of gas
development projects are under way.
</P>
<P>
During the next decade or so, they said, "market forces will be
prevalent in the decision-making process leading to large gas
export projects in the Middle East."
</P>
<P>
In the first decade of the 21st century, the Middle East's
share of world gas exports, either by pipeline or in the form of
liquified natural gas, is bound to rise considerably, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
