<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Memorial to Chinese, American Pilots To Be Built in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan
province has plans to build a memorial hall in its capital city of
Kunming, to the historical contributions of Chinese and American
pilots during World War Two.
</P>
<P>
It will contain wreckage of a military cargo plane discovered
earlier this year on Gaoligong Mountain by two hunters. The right
wing was broken off by a tree, part of the left wing broken off,
and the fuselage destroyed, but the characters for "China
Airlines" can be seen clearly.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts verify that it flew the "hump" over Burma
carrying war supplies during China's anti-Japanese war from 1937
to 1945. It crashed on March 31, 1943. The captain was American
and two other crew member were a Hong Kong man and a Cantonese.
</P>
<P>
According to Chinese authorities on World War Two, the air
route between Kunming and India's Assam State was regarded as the
most dangerous air route in the world. The 1,100-km route passed
over the southern side of the Himalayas. The peaks there are very
high and planes had to navigate among them. Because the terrain
along the route resembled the back of a camel, the route came to
be called the "hump".
</P>
<P>
During World War Two, about 70 tons of cargo were sent to China
across this very dangerous air route, greatly contributing to
China's anti-Japanese war, and 514 planes, more than 400 of which
were American, crashed on the perilous route in a three-year
period, taking the lives of some 1,500 crew members, about 1,400
of whom were Americans.
</P>
<P>
To commemorate the friendship of the American people and the
assistance given in wartime, Yunnan province decided to build a
memorial hall and a special monument for the "hump" flights in a
suburban Kunming park.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Seeks Higher OPEC Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria, Africa's number one oil
producer, now seeks to aggressively raise its crude oil
production quota set by the Organization of Petroleum Export
Countries (OPEC), the daily Champion reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said Nigeria's OPEC quota has remained static at
1.865 million barrels per day (BPD) since 1984, while the actual
production had hit 2.2 million BPD last December and further rose
to 2.34 million BPD by mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
The country's oil production is expected to increase further
in the future, with the finding of new oil on the sea, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian authorities projected that the country's oil
production would hit three million BPD by the year 2000, and
shoot to four million by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
However, the paper said, Nigeria's possibility of having
substantial increases in its OPEC allocation is doubtful, given
the projection that demand for OPEC oil which is currently about
28 million BPD will rise by a marginal seven million by the year
2010.
</P>
<P>
As 10 other OPEC countries are also demanding quota rises, the
possibility of Nigeria being such a leeway is doubted in OPEC
circles, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It gave the example of Saudi Arabia, which has a production
capacity of 12 million BPD, but is allocated only eight million.
</P>
<P>
Chief Mike Olorunfemi, former OPEC director of research and
senior official of the Nigeria National Petroleum Corporation,
projected that the world demand for crude oil would rise by only
four to five million BPD between now and the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
According to him, environmental considerations, improved
energy efficiency and increased usage of alternative energy
resources will check the demand for crude oil.
</P>
<P>
While Asia's strong economic growth will help prop up the
world demand, the report equally pointed out that former Soviet
Union and other arising oil producers will compete for the market
share with OPEC countries.
</P>
<P>
Given the gloomy possibility of a substantial rise in its
quota and the great dependence of the national economy on oil
income, the country's long-term planning body, Vision 2010
Committee has examined the scenario of Nigeria's pulling out of
the OPEC, the report said. But no further details about this were
given. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
