<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Eliminating Root of Refugee Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China has always maintained that
the refugee problems should be solved by eliminating the root
causes and providing humanitarian protection and assistance, said
Meng Xianying, head of the Chinese delegation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the annual meeting of the Executive Committee of
the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) here
today, she said that peace and development, the two major tasks
facing the international community, are also important
preconditions for the solution to the refugee problems.
</P>
<P>
"Only by seeking peaceful settlement of disputes, promoting
economic and social development, eliminating poverty and
establishing a fair and rational new international economic order
can we create the necessary political and economic conditions for
the thorough solution to refugee problems," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said that the international community should adhere to the
principle of international solidarity and burden sharing by
providing humanitarian protection and assistance to refugees ad
creating conditions for the voluntary repatriation, local
integration or resettlement of refugees.
</P>
<P>
"This requires the concerted efforts of the countries of
origin, asylum countries, and countries of resettlement as well as
donors and the relevant international organizations," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said that China stands for voluntary repatriation and calls
on the international community to actively promote the ideal and
most practical solution.
</P>
<P>
"In order to avoid forcible repatriation of refugees to the
countries of origin where conditions for return are not ready,
asylum countries should respect the principle of non-refoulement
and fulfill the obligation of protecting refugees," she said.
</P>
<P>
She urged the international community to support the asylum
countries in protecting refugees through sharing the heavy burden
of those economically backward developing countries hosting large
refugee populations.
</P>
<P>
When the domestic political and economic situation of the
countries of origin so permits, these countries should assume the
responsibility to accept refugees who volunteer to return and help
them reintegrate into the society, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
