overheating that has built up in some economies (in East Asia),"
he said, quoting the World Bank as judging that Philippines has
weathered the currency crisis "pretty well."
</P>
<P>
"Given the slowdown we expect from the combined effects of the
regional currency turmoil, we have scaled down our forecast for
GNP (gross national product) growth this year from 7.5 percent
down to 5.5 percent to 6.5 percent. This rate -- while below last
year's 6.8 percent -- should keep us well within the East Asian
league," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
According to the president, the Philippines has been
experiencing a surge in investments, which have so far multiplied
more than five times over last year's total.
</P>
<P>
Some 150 major reform laws have been enacted in the country
during the last five years -- 63 of them on economic reform, 57 on
social reform and 38 on political reform, Ramos said, adding that
"all of these laws have resulted in a more open market system."
</P>
