<HEADLINE> French Guard Injured in Brazzaville Shelling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A French military guard was
slightly injured today by shells which fell near the residence of
French ambassador in Brazzaville, capital of the Republic of
Congo, reported Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
The residence of French ambassador was located in a district
controlled by Congolese President Pascal Lissouba and his ally,
Mayor of Brazzaville Bernard Kolelas, who are waging a war with
their rival, General Denis Sassou-Nguesso.
</P>
<P>
About 30 French military police are staying in Brazzaville to
guard the French embassy in central Brazzaville and the residence
of the ambassador, Bernard Cesaire.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about 50 French expatriates living in the
Pointe-Noire, a port city west of Brazzaville still controlled by
the forces of President Lissouba, were banned from leaving the
town by "Congolese military authorities," the report quoted French
consul in Pointe-Noire as saying.
</P>
<P>
"For three days, about 50 French civilians have been going to
the airport of Pointe-Noire to quit the city. They were prevented
from taking the planes," said the consul in a communique.
</P>
<P>
About 1,600 Frenchmen and 250 other foreigners are living in
Pointe-Noire, a main base of oil exploration of the Elf-Aquitaine
oil group of France.
</P>
<P>
No explanation had been given by "competent Congolese
authorities," the consul said, and the decision to stop the
Frenchmen from leaving was made by "a military authority instead
of the authorities really exercising the power in Pointe-Noire."
</P>
<P>
Pointe-Noire is calm now and there is no problem of security
there, it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a dozen other Frenchmen and some others were
prevented from leaving two other Congolese cities, Dolisie and
Nkayi, by local military authorities, the AFP report said. 
</P>
