<HEADLINE> Ramos Expects East Asia to Resume High Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos said here today that he expects the whole of East Asia to
resume its high growth after the recent currency turmoil, noting
that the economic fundamentals of the region remain strong.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Sixth East Asian Economic Summit organized by
the World Economic Forum in the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center, Ramos pointed to the possibility of turning
this financial crisis into an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
"We expect the whole of East Asia to resume its high growth
after this turmoil," the Philippine president said. "We expect
investors to be looking more closely at the political and
socio-economic regimes of East Asia from now on."
</P>
<P>
He said the question before this three-day summit, as it was
before the world's financial leaders last month here at the World
Bank/International Monetary Fund Annual Meetings, is whether or
not the currency turmoil is a turning point on the path of high
growth for the East Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
"The short answer is 'no'," Ramos emphasized.
</P>
<P>
He explained: "First, the economic fundamentals of the
countries of the region still are strong. And there still is a lot
of room for opportunity and benefit in their strategic effort to
catch up with the more advanced nations."
</P>
<P>
"Second, the security underpinning regional stability is still
in place. And it is increasingly bolstered by the economic
independence being generated by the market system that nearly all
our (East Asian) countries have adopted," he added.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the World Bank has just forecast an average gross
domestic product growth rate of 7.6 percent for East Asia over
1997-2006, he said, noting that the figure, although low compared
with those of the early 1990s, will still make East Asia the
fastest-growing region in the world over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
However, Ramos warned, the next year or two will be difficult
for some countries in the region. But he said, quoting a Chinese
proverb, "Deep worry inspires wisdom."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
