<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bright Outlook for East Asia Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- In spite of the recent
financial instability battering East Asia, bankers attending an
economic summit here were still bullish over the region's
long-term economic growth provided adjustment policy is adopted by
governments.
</P>
<P>
Five senior banking executives were present at a panel
discussion today entitled "Is the era of fast growth over in East
Asia?" as part of the East Asia Economic Summit held between
October 13 and 15.
</P>
<P>
Manu Bhaskaran, director of SocGen-Crosby, a renowned
investment bank in Singapore, pointed out that the recent
financial crisis didn't break out overnight, and instead it was an
inescapable result of accumulation of economic strains after years
of high growth.
</P>
<P>
The crisis will bring about an adjustment policy to be
implemented for about 18 months, he said, predicting that the
regional economy will return to the fast growth track in the
second half of 1999 as a result of good economic fundamentals and
a long tradition of high savings rate.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth Courtis, first vice-president from Deutsche Bank Group
Asia, Japan, told the discussion that Southeast Asia's problem is
an emerging market problem.
</P>
<P>
His prescription is to liberalize the economy further, tighten
supervision, and increase investment in education and other sectors
with a vital bearing on the economic development.
</P>
<P>
If the "open approach" is adopted, the long-term outlook for
Southeast Asia is "fantastic", he said.
</P>
<P>
British-funded Jardine Matheson, as a group based in Hong Kong,
has participated in Asia's development for quite a long time.
According to the group's managing director Alasdair Morrison, the
recent crisis is "not the end of the growth". But he noted,
"growth itself is not enough, the important thing is the quality
of that growth."
</P>
<P>
His company views East Asia as "an exciting place to do
business" in the long term, he said.
</P>
<P>
The optimistic sentiment was shared by Mitsuo Sato, president
of the Asian Development Bank and Gautam Kaji, managing director
of the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
East Asia doesn't lose its steam as fundamentals underlining
the growth "continue to be strong", Sato said, while Kaji believed
that "we will enter into the next millennium with the bulk of East
Asia seeing better and stronger growth."
</P>
<P>
But the two businessmen pointed out that the region is facing
challenges such as an aging population, globalization and capital
market development.
</P>
<P>
The three-day East Asia Economic Summit was organized by the
Geneva-based World Economic Forum in partnership with the Hong
Kong Trade Development Council, with the theme being "the
Asia-Europe-America triangle: building networks for growth".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
