<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Softer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares closed
marginally lower today in a market lacking direction and looking
overseas for leads, and the market appeared cautious over spending
data due from the US this week.
</P>
<P>
September US retail sales figures are to be released in the US
tonight. The retail sales figures will be followed by business
inventories on Thursday and housing starts and industrial
production/capacity utilization on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said investors were holding back ahead of the float of
telecommunication giant Telstra Corp next month. "Telstra has
really taken a lot of money out of the market," they said.
</P>
<P>
"People continuing to sell the market down to pay for Telstra
was the main feature today," said Gordon Barrett of Henderson
Charlton Jones Ltd. "It was a pretty lackluster day, (with) no
driving influence."
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished 1.3 points lower at 2662.0.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 345.57 million shares, valued at 988.13
million Australian dollars (728.63 million US dollars), with falls
exceeding rises by 658 to 446.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was down 0.7 points at 1318.8, while
the all industrials was 1.9 points softer at 4370.2.
</P>
<P>
Market leader BHP eased three cents and Rio Tinto gained 14.9
cents, while Woodside Petroleum was down 16 cents.
</P>
<P>
The banking index gained 14.4 points to 5242.8, with ANZ
lifting 14 cents and CBA picking up nine, while NAB went against
the trend, slipping 13 cents.
</P>
<P>
Despite increased activity today, the gold index eased 2.3
points to 1325.6. Gold bullion was trading around 1.10 weaker at
328.00 US dollars an ounce.  
</P>
