<HEADLINE> CIS Participants Expects Closer Ties with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Participants from the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) at the ongoing 15th World
Petroleum Congress (WPS) showed strong wishes to increased
cooperation with China's petroleum industry.
</P>
<P>
Ander Gorbunov, head of the New Technology's Center of Russian
Oil and Gas Research Institute, told Xinhua that "our institute
had good cooperation with China in the past, and we once lend a
hand in the exploration of such large Chinese oilfields as Karamay
Oilfield. Wang Tao, ex-president of the China National Petroleum
Corporation, paid a visit to our department only one month ago. We
expected the cooperation between the two sides could enter a new
phase in the future."
</P>
<P>
Grygorily Brazhyna, vice-president of the State Committee of
Oil, Gas and Oil Refining Industry of Ukraine, deemed that China's
petroleum industry has made remarkable achievements after the
country initiated its reform and opening-up drive. "Even though
the two countries have not yet conducted any project, we can
further our understanding of China's oil industry through the
WPC," he said. Before the congress, he had already visited the
Dagang Oilfield in north China's Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan is China's important partner in the domain of oil
and gas exploration. The governments of the two countries recently
signed three documents, namely the agreements on state-level oil
and gas cooperation, joint exploration and development of Uzen
Oilfield in Kazakhstan, and laying of a 3,000-km oil pipeline
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the recent three documents signed between the
governments of the two countries were of international
significance, Sarmurzina, head of the eight-member Kazakhstan
delegation, said that "we are convinced that Sino-Kazakhstan
cooperation in the 21st century will have wide prospects and great
potentials," she said.
</P>
<P>
Other delegations from CIS attending the 15th WPC include
Russia, Uzbekistan, Kirghizstan and Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
Apart from China's cooperative efforts that have made with
Russian and Kazakhstan, Chinese workers have also undertaken to
repair 100 oil wells and conduct anti-sand projects in the western
part of Turkmenistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
