<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family Relationships, Major Concern of Australian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Australian children yearned
for more affection and understanding from their parents at a time
when family relationships were under increasing pressure, a new
national survey showed today.
</P>
<P>
A study of phone calls to Kids Help Line over four years also
showed an alarming increase in the number of callers who said they
had attempted or at least contemplated suicide.
</P>
<P>
Suicide still represented just over one percent of all calls
received, the Australian Associated Press said.
</P>
<P>
"The most common theme in these calls is the need for more
affection and time from parents," Kids Help Line Research Manager
Wendy Reid said.
</P>
<P>
The study showed more than one-third of calls received in the
past four years centered on concerns about family relationships,
particularly with parents.
</P>
<P>
Kids Help Line, which celebrates four years as a national
counseling service for young people this year, has answered about
440,000 phone calls in that time.
</P>
<P>
Young females represented the largest proportion of callers to
the service, making 70 percent of all calls received.
</P>
<P>
More than half the callers were aged between 10 and 14 with the
majority of callers from the larger states -- New South Wales,
Queensland, Victoria and Western Australia.
</P>
<P>
Other significant issues of concern to Australia's youth were
sex-related, with pregnancy and contraception representing a
significant proportion of calls, Reid said.
</P>
<P>
But of deep concern was a 37 percent increase over four years
in the proportion of calls received specifically about suicide.
</P>
<P>
Thirty percent of these callers reported having attempted
suicide at least once in the past, with 22 percent reporting an
immediate intention to harm themselves, the study found.
</P>
<P>
Reid said the figures were alarming and would provide the basis
for a in-depth report to be released next year under the federal
government's Youth Suicide Prevention Project.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of calls, meanwhile, relating to child abuse
declined from 11.3 percent in 1993 to 7.7 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Problems at school, particularly victims of bullying, was also
an increasing concern among callers.
</P>
<P>
Other issues of concern to children were drugs, self-esteem and
self-image, eating disorders, grief and employment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
