<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Israel to Jointly Make Missiles: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Israel are planning a
joint project to produce Delilah long-range missiles, local
newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Israeli Defense Forces Chief of Staff Amnon Lipkin
Shahak and his Turkish counterpart Ismail Hakki Karadayi discussed
the issue during their Monday meeting, a senior military official
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that
Turkey and Israel have been planning to produce long-range
missiles due to their concerns over the rising missile threat
from Iraq, Syria and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are expected to reach an agreement on the
production of the Delilah missile with a range of up to 500
kilometers, he added.
</P>
<P>
On a return visit for the one to Israel by Karadayi last
February, Shahak arrived here last Sunday on a three-day visit to
Turkey aimed at enhancing bilateral military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Shahak is believed to have persuaded the Turkish military to
replace its tank units with Israeli-made Merkava 3 tanks, one of
the world's most advanced types.
</P>
<P>
The specific arrangement of a joint naval exercises involving
Turkey, U.S. and Israel slated for November or later is also a
major topic for Shahak's talks with Turkish officials, newspaper
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli military chief's tour has drawn great attention
from the Arab countries, which have expressed their grave
concerns over the rapidly expanding Turkish-Israeli military
alliance.
</P>
<P>
In a move to downplay the Israeli military chief's Ankara
tour, Turkish Foreign Ministry Spokesman Sermet Atacanli said
Monday that Shahak's visit is a regular one.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government had repeatedly stated that the
Turkish-Israeli cooperation in military field is not directed
against any other countries.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral military cooperation was initialed in February
last year, when the two countries signed a strategic agreement in
which Turkey allowed Israeli pilots to train in its
airspace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
