<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Continue Fuel Import </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The importation of petroleum
products which began last June in Nigeria in the heat of the
acute fuel scarcity is to continue until April next year.
</P>
<P>
The move is to allow time for the refurbishment of the
nation's four on-and-off refineries which either have broken down
or are operating under half capacity, Petroleum Resources
Minister Chief Dan Etete said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
There are four refineries in Nigeria which were built seven to
32 years ago with total daily capacity of 445,000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
Because of the old age and lack of regular maintenance due to
fund shortage, most of the units of the four refineries are
either out of order or become obsolete.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the production has been reduced to half of their
capacity, which caused acute fuel scarcity that slowed down
business activities in many parts of the country, especially
between March and July this year.
</P>
<P>
The government had to resort to import to ease the situation,
and part of the foreign product was recently confirmed by the
Environmental Protection Agency to be toxic, producing a bad odor
hazardous to people's health.
</P>
<P>
As part of the efforts to put the refineries back in good
shape, the government has signed a 200-million-U.S.-Dollar
agreement to allow the French oil company Total to repair and run
the Kaduna Refinery for two years.
</P>
<P>
Oil giants Mobil and Shell have jointly carried out a
technical assessment of the maintenance work, saying that the
entire job will cost one billion Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report of the study is now being considered by the
Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation and the National Economic
Intelligence Committee.
</P>
<P>
As it will take months to finish maintenance of a plant, the
deadline for importation, originally scheduled for September, has
to be extended. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
