<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Spends Over $1 Billion on Refugee Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong has spent more than
one billion U.S. dollars on the Vietnamese refugee and migrant
program since 1975, said a Hong Kong official.
</P>
<P>
Sally Wong, who represents the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region government in the Chinese delegation, said today that with
a land area of a little over 1,000 square kilometers, Hong Kong
has provided first asylum to over 200,000 Vietnamese since 1975.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the efforts of the UNHCR and the resettlement
countries, some 143,000 Vietnamese refugees have been resettled
over the years, she told the Executive Committee annual meeting of
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
About 67,000 migrants have been screened out as non-refugees
and returned to Vietnam through either the UNHCR Voluntary
Repatriation Program or the Orderly Repatriation Program run by
the Hong Kong government, she said.
</P>
<P>
"The cost of the Vietnamese refugee and migrant program to Hong
Kong has often been ignored or underestimated," she said. "We have
spent 8.17 billion HK dollars (over one billion dollars) by way of
direct expenditure on the program."
</P>
<P>
In addition to this, Hong Kong has advanced to the UNHCR
another 1.17 billion HK dollars (150 million dollars), she said
</P>
<P>
Apart from this fairly heavy financial burden, she said, Hong
Kong has also contributed to resolving the problem as a place of
resettlement.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1970s, Hong Kong absorbed some 14,000 displaced
people from Indo-China. About 1,700 boatpeople have been resettled
in Hong Kong under various schemes since that period.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are still about 1,300 Vietnamese refugees,
800 Vietnamese non-refugees and over 1,000 Vietnamese illegal
immigrants in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
She said that the UNHCR is actively pursuing resettlement
opportunities for the refugees remaining in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
She called on the international community to help resettle this
final group of Vietnamese refugees stranded in Hong Kong for
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
