<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Gas Trade to Grow Five Percent Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- International gas trade is
expected to grow at an average annual rate of nearly five percent
in the next 15 years as world gas consumption expands, according
to the ongoing 15th World Petroleum Congress here.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, international gas trade will amount to 400 to
510 billion cubic meters, compared to 396 billion cubic meters in
1995, Olivier Appert, a senior researcher with the French
Institute of Petroleum, said at a forum of the congress this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The figure will continue to rise to 710 to 730 billion cubic
meters by the year 2010, Appert said.
</P>
<P>
"After more than two decades of steady and sustained growth,"
he noted, "worldwide natural gas demand shows bright prospects for
further expansion."
</P>
<P>
He forecast that natural gas share in world energy balances will
increase up to 25 percent by 2010, compared to 23 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Natural gas is seen as a clean fuel, with powerful and
appreciated assets when compared with other fossil fuels, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the increase in the use of gas is closely linked to
the performances of gas technologies, mainly in the power generation
sector where the use of gas in combined cycle power plants and in
cogeneration is developing rapidly, he said.
</P>
<P>
Annual gas demand worldwide should reach around 2,500 billion
cubic metres by the year 2000 and around 3,000 billion cubic
metres by 2010, compared to 2,200 billion cubic metres in 1995,
Appert said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to note that such a global gas expansion will
concern all geographic areas, including the four main markets of
North America, Europe, the Commonwealth of Independent States
(CIS) and the Far East.
</P>
<P>
Gas expansion will be more pronounced in the developing
countries than in the traditional markets, especially in Asia
where robust economic growth leads to stronger gas demand, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
