<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Central Bank Increases Duration of Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese central bank has
moved to loosen credit restrictions on some businesses by increasing
the duration of loans for operational funds.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China has called for commercial banks to
grant more loan support to large profitable enterprises
with normal production orders, a proven market for their products
and adequate capacity to pay debts.
</P>
<P>
The longest term of loans for operational funds was capped at
one year in the past. The bank has now increased that limit up to
three years.
</P>
<P>
Analysts hailed the extended loan term as a move to improve
financial services and agreed that it would play an active role in
boosting the economy.
</P>
<P>
Under the new definitions, the bank loans fall into three
categories: temporary loans for three months or less; short-term
loans between three months and one year; and medium-term loans
from one to three years.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates for the medium-term loans for operational funds
will be the same as for loans for fixed assets. For the
state-designated 512 large and medium-sized state enterprises, as
well as some others with state support, no increase in interest
rates will be permitted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
