<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 09:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Economic Growth Slows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Israel's economy is estimated
to grow at a lower annual rate of 2 percent for this year in
comparison with the 4 percent of last year, according to latest
figures by Israeli Central Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The figures, based on actual results in the first three
quarters and predictions for the final three months of the year,
suggest a per capita GDP of nearly 60,000 shekels (about 17,140
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
But trade situation is expected to improve for the year, as a 6
percent growth is estimated in exports, compared to a 5 percent
growth in 1996. And the growth in imports of goods and services
will reach 3 percent, compared to an 8 percent increase in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The fixed asset investments in construction and equipment,
which witnessed considerable growth over the previous three years,
are set to shrink, the statistics report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
