<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Researchers Test New Flu Cure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli researchers have for
the first time immunized a group of old people against the flu
with a nose drop containing killed strains of the flu virus.
</P>
<P>
The clinical trials were conducted by Professors Zichria Zakay
Rones and Reuven Levy from the Viology Department of the Hebrew
University's Hadassah Medical School in Jerusalem, English daily
The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The nose drop, developed by Rones and Levy after years of
search for a new form of flu vaccine, is meant to create
antibodies to the flu virus in the respiratory system, through
which it enters the body and blood to provide extra protection.
</P>
<P>
It was hoped that the new clinical trials would lead to an
easy-to-use weapon against the flu. Last year, the nose drop was
proven successful in protecting healthy medical students against
the disease.
</P>
<P>
Now the medicine is being tried on a group of elderly, whose
immune systems do not react fully to an injected vaccine, but who
are most at risk for complications of the flu.
</P>
<P>
If the nose drop proves effective among the elderly, it could
save them from pneumonia and other infections that result from
flu, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Banks Urged to Fund Small Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October (Xinhua) -- A three-day conference, organized
by Lebanese central bank and the banks association, urged
bankers to extend loans to small businesses, Lebanese
English-language newspaper the Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speakers from international banks, including representatives
from Egypt, the United States and Germany, highlighted the
potential for lending to small businesses.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the conference, which opened Monday, said that
in other parts of the world, small business loans are mostly
extended by banks.
</P>
<P>
In Lebanon, however, the majority of the estimated 3 million
U.S. dollars of small loans is provided by non-governmental
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The paper said banks in Lebanon have been reluctant to lend
to small enterprises because the banks are used to dealing with
established businesses, and lending on collateral basis.
</P>
<P>
Judith Brandsma, a World Bank specialist, said Lebanese banks
would have to toughen up their collection procedures when
dealing with small businesses.
</P>
<P>
"Banks have to be tough and serious, knocking on the
shoulders of borrowers if they are one day late," she
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
