<HEADLINE> Northeast China City Seeking Donations to Expand Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Shenyang, a city in northeast
China, is seeking donations to expand the September 18 Incident
Museum, which marks the Japanese invasion of China in 1931.
</P>
<P>
The museum includes a monument and a 600-square-meter
exhibition hall. Last month, city officials announced a plan to
add 15,000 square meters to serve as a living textbook for
education about patriotism.
</P>
<P>
Statements soliciting donations have appeared in local
newspapers and on TV shows calling for support from local
residents as well as people from Hong Kong, Macao, Taiwan and
overseas donors.
 The city will give commemorative medals and cards or carve names
into a monument in the new exhibition hall.
</P>
<P>
The Central Military Commission and the State Bureau of
Cultural Relics are also expected to provide financial support,
local officials said.
</P>
<P>
The project is scheduled to be completed in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
