<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Gas Industry Needs One Trillion USD investment: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The worldwide expansion of the gas
industry will require a total capital investment of about 1,000
billion U.S. dollars over the next 20 years, a leading petroleum
researcher said here today.
</P>
<P>
The industry needs the huge investment to produce, transport and
store the quatities of gas, Olivier Appert, a senior researcher with
the French Institute of Petroleum, told a forum of the ongoing 15th
World Petroleum Congress this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Appert estimated that the industry is expected to build 500,000
to 700,000 km of gas transmission lines and more than two million
km of distribution lines in the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The gas chain is in fact highly capital intensive, he said,
adding that a long-distance pipeline with a capacity of 30 billion
cubic meters a year requires an investment of 10 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Currently, more than 85 projects representing about 142,600 km,
equivalent to more than three trips round the world, are being
contemplated worldwide to accompany the growth in international
trade, he said.
</P>
<P>
International projects with a short-term completion date will
generate an additional export capacity, mainly to Europe, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, new grassroots projects will be necessary to ensure
the progression of liquified natural gas trade. Appert said that
nearly 20 projects are being set forth at present, but they
haven't entered the state of development yet.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that gas projects are likely to face a
shortage of available capital, due both to the competition of many
other infrastructure projects, especially in Eastern Europe and
Asia, as well as the reduction of financial possibilities of the
traditional lender companies.
</P>
<P>
"Faced with the huge sums to be invested and the extremely long
period required for setting up new gas projects, only those
offering a good rate of return and incurring limited risks will
find the necessary financing," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
