<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Speed Up Rural Development Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government will
allocate 50 million Zimbabwe Dollars (four $million) to each of
the country's 10 provinces for rural development projects this
financial year, President Robert Mugabe has said.
</P>
<P>
He told hundreds of ruling ZANU (PF) officials at a meeting in
Gwanda, south Zimbabwe Monday that he directed the Ministry of
Finance to make provisions in the budget for rural development.
</P>
<P>
"For a start, 50 million will be earmarked for development
projects in each province. I want to see the money go into
projects," he said.
</P>
<P>
None of the money, he stressed, would go toward payment of
salaries. It would only be used on actual projects.
</P>
<P>
He said that while the land was important, there was need to
develop projects in rural areas like water for irrigation.
</P>
<P>
"There can be no development in rural areas unless we empower
the people. We have to give the people the means to use the
land," he explained, adding that the Ministry of Rural Resources
and Water Development had been set up, especially to spearhead
development in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe started his one-week-long meet-the-people tour which
will cover the country's eight provinces. 
</P>
