<HEADLINE> French Oil Developers Want Increased Cooperation with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- French oil developers attending
the 15th World Petroleum Congress (WPC) have voiced a strong
desire for closer ties with their Chinese counterparts.
</P>
<P>
"ELF group expects a fourfold increase in sales in China by the
year 2000," said Antoine Jonglas, senior vice-president of the
Department of Refining and Marketing Business Development of the
ELF, a large international oil company in France.
</P>
<P>
The ELF sold 44.8 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil products
last year, making it one of the top 10 private oil and natural gas
companies in the world, Jonglas said, adding that his company will
work in cooperation with China on more than 40 projects, including
a lubricator production base in Guangzhou and petroleum products
sales in Zhengzhou.
</P>
<P>
Another leading French oil company, TOTAL, is expected to
provide liquefied natural gas to China, and to jointly develop a
transport network for natural gas, according to Gerare Choux,
representative of TOTAL China Company.
</P>
<P>
Choux cited TOTAL as one of the first companies engaged in oil
drilling and production in China, and said that its technology
caters to the country's needs.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, another official from the French Petroleum
Institution expressed optimism about the development of the
Chinese market, which he said is "full of vigor."  
</P>
