<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Urged to Curb Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has been
urged to increase fraud penalties to curb vices like smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Two visiting World Customs Organization (WCO) technical
advisors said here Monday that Zambia, like many other developing
countries, is losing huge sums of money from transit fraud and
smuggling and therefore needs to increase criminal penalties, the
Times of Zambia reported today.
</P>
<P>
One of the two, Harry Waskiewicz, said, "customs should become
an agency to protect borders against the bringing in of
contraband like drugs. But right now customs are concentrating on
collecting revenue," said Waskiewicz.
</P>
<P>
He said communication equipment and record systems between
ports need to be improved for increased monitoring.
</P>
<P>
Zambia suffers most from smuggling and transit fraud where
goods passing through are diverted, off-loaded secretly and sold,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia has geographical problems because of the vast
land border and it is therefore prudent to station customs
officers alongside or increase mobile anti-smuggling teams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crocodiles Kill 32 Ugandans on Victoria Shores </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-two Ugandans have been
killed by crocodiles on the islands and shores of Lake Victoria
over the last six months, reported local daily "The New Vision"
today.
</P>
<P>
Florence Oundo, a local official on Sigulu islands on the lake
was quoted as saying that the latest incident occurred on
Wednesday when a crocodile grabbed a seven-year-old girl as she
fetched water.
</P>
<P>
Oundo said the crocodiles have killed four people in Maluba,
three in Matolo and two in Lubango.
</P>
<P>
Siragi Lyavala, another local official, was quoted as
appealing to the central government to reduce the crocodile
population to save the people's lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
