<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Suicide Foreigners Attack Philippine Military Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Two foreign suicide bombers
today attacked an army camp in the southern Philippines, killing
three soldiers before being shot dead, military spokesman Captain
Noel Detoyato said.
</P>
<P>
The bombers were identified as an Egyptian man and his
colleague who was holding "Saudi Arabian-Pakistani" travel papers,
Detoyato said, adding the attackers were aided by two Filipinos
who later fled the scene.
</P>
<P>
He said the attack on the camp was believed to be the first of
its kind involving foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The two bombers first killed the camp sentry and then forced
their way into the camp in South Cotabato province, armed with two
bags full of grenades, Detoyato said.
</P>
<P>
They began to fire guns and throw grenades when found by the
camp defenders, killing two more soldiers before being shot dead,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The military believed that the two foreigners were working with
the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF), a 10,000-member rebel
group which has been waging a separatist campaign in the southern
part of the country.
</P>
<P>
The MILF opened low-level peace talks with the government
earlier this year, but the two sides so far have made little
progress toward forging a peace deal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
