<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Petroleum Exploration Theory Paying Off in Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- After four decades of research
and practice, China has explored and developed a number of large
oil and gas fields based on a unique petroleum exploration
theory, according to a senior oil official.
</P>
<P>
Wang Tao, senior adviser to the China National Petroleum
Corporation (CNPC), told Xinhua on Monday at the 15th
World Petroleum Congress, that the contents of the "oil
exploration theory with Chinese characteristics" include
research on continental petroleum geology, multi-layered oil and
gas concentration belts, Guqianshan oil and gas reserves, marine
oil and gas reserves found in Paleozoic Era levels, and
continental deposits found in Mesozoic and Cenozoic era geologic
layers.
</P>
<P>
China has verified five billion tons of recoverable oil
reserves by using the theory of continental petroleum geology,
Wang said. Seventyfive percent of the reserves are in China's
large oil fields, whose annual output usually exceeds 20 million
tons each.
</P>
<P>
The exploration and development of Daqing and other large
oil fields in China have ratified the theory of continental petroleum
geology, he said. Currently, 95 percent of China's crude oil and 44
percent of its natural gas come from the fields found by using
the theory.
</P>
<P>
Using the theory on multi-layered oil and gas concentration and
rolling development techniques, Chinese geologists have developed
160 oil fields in north China's Bohai Sea region, whose geological
structure is complicated.
</P>
<P>
Chinese geologists have detected more than 40 oil-bearing areas
in Renqiu and the Dongshengbu-Jing'anbu belt of north China by
using the Guqianshan oil and gas reserve theory.
</P>
<P>
Based on the study of sedimentary rock formed during the
Paleozoic Era (570 to 230 million years ago), China has found
recoverable oil reserves in the Sichuan, Tarim and
Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia basins.
</P>
<P>
Wang said Chinese scientists in recent years have made
breakthroughs in knowledge about the formation and distribution of
oil and gas reserves. Geological surveys have proved that large
gas fields similar to those in Canada's Alberta could be found in
China.
</P>
<P>
China by early next century could build up a number of large
bases with annual production ranging from 5 billion to 10 billion
cubic meters in Sichuan, Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia, Xinjiang and the
South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
"China's oil exploration theory and practices indicate that
petroleum exploration in the country is promising," Wang
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
