<HEADLINE> Japan Helps Uganda in Improving Water Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Japan has granted Uganda
45,000 U.S. Dollars to improve hygienic water supply in the
country's southern district of Rakai, reported ''the Monitor''
paper today.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Charge d'Affairs to Uganda Yonego Otake was quoted as
saying that his country granted the money to Uganda to assist the
district in carrying out its wells-drilling project in rural
communities.
</P>
<P>
He said the district has suffered from civil war, disease and
poverty, adding that it is an urgent need to provide villagers
with safe drinking water.
</P>
<P>
Otake said the grant will be used for purchasing materials and
engineering costs for the construction of the 65 shallow wells in
the district.
</P>
<P>
These wells will contribute to reduce epidemics through water
and relieve women and children from the heavy labor associated
with drawing water from unhygienic sources, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
