<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Cases Up in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Reported cases of people with
AIDS in Uganda have gone up by over 100 percent from 48,312 in
1995 to 99,656 between 1996 and 1997, reported local daily "The
Monitor" today.
</P>
<P>
A HIV/AIDS surveillance report issued by the Ministry of
Health in October this year was quoted as saying a cumulative
total of 48,312 cases were reported in 1995, adding that majority
of the cases were Ugandans above 12 years while 3,754 were
children below 11.
</P>
<P>
By December 1996, a cumulative total of 51,344 cases were
reported to the Surveillance Unit, of which 47,555 were people
above 12 years, while 3,789 were children below 12, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the reported cases represent a small fraction of
the actual number of AIDS cases in the country.
</P>
<P>
Opio Alex, an epidemiologist in the Health Ministry was quoted
as saying that about 95 percent of AIDS cases are acquired
through sexual transmission.
</P>
<P>
It is now a decade and a half since the first cases of AIDS
disease were reported in Uganda. And now Uganda ranks top in
Africa in suffering AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
