<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Oil, Gas Demand Expected to Remain Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The demand for petroleum and
natural gas is expected to remain stable, said a senior official
at the 15th World Petroleum Congress (WPC).
</P>
<P>
Miguel Bechelli, vice-president of WPC, told Xinhua Monday that
the price of crude oil is expected to fluctuate between 18 and 22
U.S. dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Petroleum will remain one of the main energy sources until the
year 2050, he predicted. "Gas production in this period will
increase, but not by a big margin," he said.
</P>
<P>
Data from western oil companies indicate that the world's
proven oil reserves in 1996 rose by 2 percent over 1995. Of those
reserves, the Middle East has 65 percent; Latin America, 12
percent; Europe, 9 percent; Africa, 6 percent; and the remaining 4
percent each in the Asia-Pacific region and North America.
</P>
<P>
Bechelli, of Argentina, said the reserves in Latin America
totaled 166 billion barrels, of which 90 percent is in Venezuela
and Mexico. "The resources in our continent allow developers to
explore for 23 years," he said, adding that the 270 billion
barrels of super-heavy oil in Venezuela may extend the development
period to 62 years.
</P>
<P>
Bechelli said that the 15th WPC offers an opportunity for China's
petroleum industry and their foreign counterparts to enhance their
mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
In the six years after Argentina was host for the 13th WPC, he
said, a large amount of foreign capital poured into that South
American country. Argentina's oil output increased by 85 percent
after that, and natural gas production by 30 percent. In 1994
Argentina became a crude oil exporter and "started to export
natural gas," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Road Accidents Rise in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Road traffic accidents in
Zambia have soared to 1,000 deaths per year and the situation may
worsen unless efforts are made to reverse the trend, "Zambia
Daily Mail" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted London Ngoma, director of the National Roads
Safety Council (NRSC), as saying here Monday that things on the
Zambian roads are getting serious and will result in a
complicated traffic situation especially in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Aeron Thomas, a road safety consultant, attributed the safety
situation to the increased number of cars on the roads coupled
with poor traffic regulation enforcement, said the daily.
</P>
<P>
Ngoma advised that to alleviate road problems on the Zambian
roads, the NRSC has taken measures to make all road traffic stake
holders have an input in a proposed road safety action plan.
</P>
<P>
She also noted that traffic law enforcement in Zambia is
inadequate because there are several loopholes that enable
offenders to get away with offenses.
</P>
<P>
A workshop will open soon to cover subjects on road safety
management, accident data system, road safety engineering,
traffic law enforcement and traffic legislation, according to the
daily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Wafer Fabrication Plant to Be Ready in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will have its
first wafer fabrication plant ready by the end of 1999 to push its
electronics industry to a new high.
</P>
<P>
The semiconductor wafer fabrication plant is a joint venture
between Malaysia's Khazanah Nasional Bhd (National Treasury
Limited) and the United States' Atmel Corporation, a leading
manufacturer of a broad range high performance, low power
non-volatile memory and logic integrated circuits, for which an
agreement was signed here today.
</P>
<P>
Khazanah, the government's investment arm, takes up 40 percent
equity in the joint venture while the other 60 percent would be
taken up by Atmel, Khazanah's managing director Mohd Sheriff Mohd
Kassim said.
</P>
<P>
The initial project cost is 830 million U.S. dollars, of which
275 million U.S. dollars will be funded by equity, he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to start ground work in February 1998
and will take about 18 months to complete.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture will process and fabricate eight-inch wafers,
using initially 0.35 micron CMOS technology and subsequently
migrating to 0.25 micron technology, thus giving Malaysia a
leading edge wafer fabrication facility.
</P>
<P>
It is capable of producing 7,000 wafers per week and generating
a revenue of 400 million U.S. dollars per year after full
production.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture has a 100 percent buy back guarantee from
Atmel for a 10 year period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
