<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Seek Ways to Curb Deterioration of Sown Pasture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists here have
succeeded in controling the degeneration of sown pasture lands in
the Yunnan-Guizhou plateau after seven years of research efforts.
</P>
<P>
The conservation of pasture in the Yunnan-Guizhou plateau has
been listed as one of the major state science and technology
research programs.
</P>
<P>
Wang Gang, a professor at a state laboratory on arid land
agro-ecology attached to Lanzhou University, said after years of
experiments his lab had discovered ways to effectively control
weeds and the deterioration of pasture land. Those methods include
fertilizers, grazing as well as weed removal.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that one-tenth hectare of pasture in the plateau was
sufficient to feed a sheep, matching the level of countries with
advanced animal husbandry such as New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Adopting the newly developed techniques, Wang said, virtually
eliminates weeds and more than 90 percent of the grass is sown
forage grain.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the Chinese government has decided to expand use of
the techniques into 25,000 hectares of sown pasture in the
Yunnan-Guizhou plateau.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, the Chinese government has promoted a
large-scale operation on developing pasture in south China. After
chopping or burning down shrubs on pasture lands in the
Yunnan-Guizhou plateau, scientists and technicians sowed quality
grass seed. One county in Guizhou province had 10,000 hectares of
forage grassland seeded by air. In the first two or three years,
the sown forage grass grew very well. However, the sown pasture
faced a large scale invasion of weeds and a reduction of forage
grass. Wang's lab dedicated years to solving the problems
hindering further development of sown pasture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
