<HEADLINE> S. African Airline to Increase Regional Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- South African Airways
(SAA) will offer additional regional flights after it acquired a
second Boeing 767 wide-bodied aircraft, local daily "The Star"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The recently leased aircraft will allow SAA to improve its
regional schedules, to introduce a fourth weekly flight between
South Africa and India and to operate six connections to
Mauritius, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"There has been a high demand for seats between South Africa
and India since the introduction of our service in March 1995,"
said Mike Myburgh, chief executive of SAA.
</P>
<P>
According to SAA officials, the Sunday flight from
Johannesburg to Cape Town, the legislative capital of South
Africa, and Windhoek, Namibia, will also be operated by a B767
airliner. 
</P>
