<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Siamese Twins Separated Successfully in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- South African doctors at
Soweto's Chris Hani Baragwanath Hospital on Monday successfully
separated two Siamese girls after a 12-hour operation, South
African press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Conditions of the Siamese twins were "very stable" after the
operation on Monday night, said Dr John da Fonseca, head of the
operation team.
</P>
<P>
"They are both doing well and have all the vital organs they
need. If they don't contract an infection, they will be out of
intensive care within four to five days," he said.
</P>
<P>
The six-month-old girls had multiple abnormalities, but they
would be able to lead normal lives, said the doctor.
</P>
<P>
The twins had been joined from the abdomen down to their legs
and had had fused genitalia, fused livers divided by a septum,
and had shared a large bowel and part of a small bowel.
</P>
<P>
Due to the absence of anuses, the doctors had to give each
twin a colostomy -- use a piece of colon to create an anus. The
pelvises of the girls were also reconstructed.
</P>
<P>
However, they were found during the operation that they were
not sharing a bladder as previously feared. They also had two
normal kidneys each.
</P>
<P>
They also had two vaginas each. Da Fonseca said they would
need both vaginas in their later years to avoid the accumulation
of menstrual blood.
</P>
<P>
The girls would have to walk with a gait because both would
have one short leg, their spines were deviated and they were
club-footed.
</P>
<P>
But these problems could be addressed with, among other
remedies, physiotherapy, Da Fonseca said.
</P>
<P>
The girls were born on April 14 and were transferred to the
hospital two days later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Gas Trade to Grow Five Percent Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- International gas trade is
expected to grow at an average annual rate of nearly five percent
in the next 15 years as world gas consumption expands, according
to the ongoing 15th World Petroleum Congress here.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, international gas trade will amount to 400 to
510 billion cubic meters, compared to 396 billion cubic meters in
1995, Olivier Appert, a senior researcher with the French
Institute of Petroleum, said at a forum of the congress this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The figure will continue to rise to 710 to 730 billion cubic
meters by the year 2000, Appert said.
</P>
<P>
"After more than two decades of steady and sustained growth,"
he noted, "worldwide natural gas demand shows bright prospects for
further expansion."
</P>
<P>
He forecast that natural gas share in world energy balances will
increase up to 25 percent by 2010, compared to 23 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Natural gas is seen as a clean fuel, with powerful and
appreciated assets when compared with other fossil fuels, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the increase in the use of gas is closely linked to
the performances of gas technologies, mainly in the power generation
sector where the use of gas in combined cycle power plants and in
cogeneration is developing rapidly, he said.
</P>
<P>
Annual gas demand worldwide should reach around 2,500 billion
cubic metres by the year 2000 and around 3,000 billion cubic
metres by 2010, compared to 2,200 billion cubic metres in 1995,
Appert said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to note that such a global gas expansion will
concern all geographic areas, including the four main markets of
North America, Europe, the Commonwealth of Independent States
(CIS) and the Far East.
</P>
<P>
Gas expansion will be more pronounced in the developing
countries than in the traditional markets, especially in Asia
where robust economic growth leads to stronger gas demand, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
