<HEADLINE> Survey Reveals Pollution Data in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A survey on industrial pollution
in the Tibet Autonomous Region of China has revealed that most of
the township enterprises in the region pose no major threat to the
environment.
</P>
<P>
The survey, the first done among some 1,000 local township
firms, says only 128 enterprises, or 10 percent of the total
surveyed, cause pollution. They are mostly mines, cement
factories, wollen mills and lumber and grain processing
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"But the scale of those enterprises are small, with some only
having a couple of people, and they are scattered in 42 counties
of seven cities," states the report. "At present they constitute
no threat to Tibet's ecological environment."
</P>
<P>
Rural firms in Tibet each year discharge 450,000 tons of
industrial waste water, 11,000 cubic meters of
waste gas and 2,000 tons of industrial dust, the survey shows.
</P>
<P>
Those enterprises also produce 51,000 tons of solid industrial
waste annually, of which more than 30,000 tons is recycled.
</P>
<P>
Ecologists say that rural firms in Tibet cause little pollution
compared with like companies in other parts of China. However,
they caution that as more township enterprises are being set up in
cities in the region, they will sooner or later
have a negative effect on its environment.
</P>
<P>
"Tibet will never develop its local economy at the cost of its
environment," said Locang Puncog, head of the Tibet Environmental
Protection Bureau. He said the local government is working on a
series of regulations on pollution control in township
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from enhanced monitoring, we will take measures to limit
the number of mines, gradually phase out outdated techniques and
equipment, and promote recycling technology," Locang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
