<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's GDP Forecast to Grow by 6.8 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian Institute of
Economic Research (MIER) has forecast that Malaysia's real gross
domestic product (GDP) will grow by 6.8 percent next year with
inflation higher at 4.8 percent, its executive director Mohamed
Ariff said here today.
</P>
<P>
The country's economic growth for this year has also been
revised downwards to 8.0 percent from 8.2 percent, he told a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
In the first and second quarters of 1997, Malaysia's real GDP
growth rates were 8.5 percent and 8.4 percent respectively
compared to the corresponding quarters in 1996, and the inflation
rate for the first half of 1997 was at less than 3 percent,
according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The sharp depreciation of the Malaysian ringgit against the
U.S. dollar and most of the other major currencies since July has
cast a cloud of uncertainty over the economic prospects for the
rest of this year, particularly in the final quarter, Mohamed
Ariff said.
</P>
<P>
However, he was confident that the export sector will continue
to grow for the rest of 1997 and 1998, although at a slower rate.
He said it was not all a bad year as the MIER had also forecast
that exports of goods and non-sector services would grow by 11.7
percent in 1998 as a result of a boost from the weaker ringgit.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, import of goods and non-sector services is
expected to grow by 10.5 percent next year with some form of
domestic substitution expected in view of the higher cost of
imports from a weak ringgit.
</P>
<P>
He said that the labor market is still expected to be in a
healthy state with unemployment rate up at 2.6 percent next year
from the present 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Private investment is projected to grow by 7.1 percent in 1998
while private consumption growth is forecast at 5.8 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
