<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Advanced Oil Sands Technology to Make Canada Growing Oil Supplier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Alberta, one of the ten
provinces and two territories in the country, has found oil sands
reserves of 1.7 billion barrels of bitumen in place, and is thus
blessed with a huge potential for large-scale exploration by using the
new-generation oil sands processing technology.
</P>
<P>
Stephen West, minister of energy of Alberta Province, made this
remark while addressing the ministerial panel of World Petroleum
Congress today.
</P>
<P>
West noted that among the province's oil sands reserves, 300
billion barrels -- the equivalent to the entire proven reserves of
Saudi Arabia -- are considered potentially recoverable.
</P>
<P>
Pioneering in oil sands extraction technologies, Alberta was the
inventor of the steam-assisted gravity drainage technology, which is
helping open up the province's oil sands to development.
</P>
<P>
The latest breakthroughs in the sands processing industry, such
as the SAG-D technology, could triple the oil sands production of Alberta
to as much as 1.2 million barrels a day, according to West.
</P>
<P>
"This would mean a total oil sands investment of up to 25 billion
US dollars over the next 20 years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Alberta now produces 905,000 barrels of conventional oil and
100,000 tons of bituminous and subbituminous coal, accounting for
72 percent and nearly 50 percent, respectively, of the total of
Canada.
</P>
<P>
The city of Calgory of Alberta Province is elected the host for
the 16th World petroleum Congress in the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
