<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Juma Appeals for Aid to Health Delivery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Vice-President
Omar Ali Juma has appealed for reduction of debt burden of
developing countries for the interest of better health delivery.
</P>
<P>
Debt burden has seriously affected provision of health
services in third world countries, Juma said when he opened the
Eight Congress of the World Federation of Public Health
Associations in Arusha on Monday, according to a news dispatch
reaching here today from the northern Tanzanian town.
</P>
<P>
He noted that developing countries needs support of the
industrialized world in providing better health care but "debt
burden has adversely affected provision of health services in
third world countries".
</P>
<P>
Juma cited example of Tanzania which is currently servicing an
external debt of more than 6.4 billion U.S. Dollars, saying that
the debt servicing is expected to reach 422.4 million US Dollars
by the end of December this year.
</P>
<P>
"Easing of debt burden is a crucial area of support," said
Juma, adding that "we cannot continue to shoulder our debt burden
and to meet our social and economic responsibilities."
</P>
<P>
He urged developed countries to meet their commitment of
setting 0.7 percent of the GDP for assistance to developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
Over 600 delegates from 50 countries are taking part in the
five-day meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
