<HEADLINE> Iran's Oil Industry Ready to Open Wider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Iran has survived the US
sanction and is actively pursuing international cooperation in its
petroleum industry, said Seyed Mehdi Hosseini, advisor to the
Minister of Petroleum on international affairs today at the 15th
World Petroleum Congress (WPC).
</P>
<P>
He said Iran recently signed two petroleum projects with
France, Malaysia and Russia, and has extended its international
cooperation to both the on-shore and off-shore sectors.
</P>
<P>
The names on Iran's favorite investor list also include China
and other members of the Commonwealth of Independent States
(CIS). Hosseini said that his country has established a sound
cooperative relations with China in petrochemical area, and will
negotiate some oil exploration projects in the near future.
</P>
<P>
He said he thought that the Iran-China cooperation in oil
exploration is of good prospectives, though it is still on a
beginning stage.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Hosseini said that his country's oil sector recovered
from the Iran-Iraq War by increasing its daily oil production
capacity from 2.4 million tons to 4.1 million tons.
</P>
<P>
In August, 1996, the United State passed a law in opposition to
no-American companies which invested 40 million dollars or more in
Iranian oil and gas sector. The investment ceiling dropped to 20
millions in last August, Hosseini said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
