<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria To Remain A Key Player in Oil Production For 40 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- With the application of
advanced techniques, a lot more oil will be found in the Niger
Delta and other basins, and Nigeria will remain a key player in
crude production for the next two decades or more and about 125
years for gas, a senior Nigerian oil official said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ministerial panel of the ongoing 15th World
Petroleum Congress here today, Chief Dan Etete, minister of
petroleum resources, said that Nigeria is the world's tenth
largest oil exporter with proven reserve of about 25 billion
barrels and 124 trillion cubic feet of gas.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that the Nigerian petroleum industry has
benefited from the world-wide technology advancement. In the
upstream operations, activities above moved from the onshore to
deeper offshore.
</P>
<P>
And hydrocarbon reserves have correspondingly increased from
about six billion barrels in the 1960s to about 25 billion barrels
of oil today, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the oil and gas industry accounts
for about 85 percent of the country's total government revenue, 95
percent of foreign earnings and 20 percent of the Gross Domestic
Product.
</P>
<P>
The official said that in line with recent growth world-wide,
the Nigerian government has continued to encourage private sector
participation in order to facilitate the development of the
petroleum industry in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He said that with average production of about 2.2 billion
barrels of oil per day, Nigerian will remain an important oil
producer and exporter in the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Urged to Further Devaluate Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has urged
Bangladesh to have a competitive exchange rate for its currency by
further devaluating the taka in relation to the U.S. dollar, now
standing at less than 45 taka to 1 dollar.
</P>
<P>
The foreign currency reserves of Bangladesh, which stood
recently at 1.7 billion dollars, were at a critical level, said
the bank's annual economic review on Bangladesh, which was
prepared for the annual Bangladesh Aid Consortium meeting
scheduled for early next month.
</P>
<P>
Calling further devaluation of the taka essential, the review
pointed out that a 4.6-percent devaluation of the currency since
July last year was not enough to outweigh a 4-percent appreciation
of the real effective exchange rate of the taka.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the country's export competitiveness did not
improve and practically eroded following sharp devaluation of
currencies in the neighboring South Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
However, owing to a healthy 14-percent export growth and a
phenomenal increase in remittances from abroad, the current
account deficit in external trade came down from over 5 percent of
the GDP during 1995-95 to less than 3 percent during the last
fiscal 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
Imports last year also declined to 3.5 percent from 18 percent
in fiscal 1995-96. The drastic decline in imports slowed down
rapid erosion of the government's foreign currency reserves.
</P>
<P>
But low aid disbursement at 1.8 billion dollars last year and a
120 million dollars capital flight from the stock market offset
further improvement in the current account deficit, said the bank.
</P>
<P>
It said pressure on foreign exchange reserves might continue
and even soar with recovery in industrial activities and ensuing
pickup demand for imports.
</P>
<P>
The report stressed the need for rebuilding the reserves and
said the competitive exchange rate would strengthen the country's
export base.
</P>
<P>
It recommended steps for improving the capital accounts
balance, saying it is essential for the country to expedite
foreign aid utilization by removing bottlenecks to project
implementation, meeting policy commitments and attracting more
private foreign capital inflows.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
