<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Queen Asks India, Pakistan to End Hostility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- British Queen Elizabeth II on
Monday called upon India and Pakistan to bury "historical
hostilities" for good, the local press said today.
</P>
<P>
The queen made the remarks even as India and Britain mounted a
damage control exercise to defuse a diplomatic row over Kashmir
which threatened to mar the third state visit to India by the
British monarch.
</P>
<P>
In her speech at a banquet hosted by Indian President Kocheril
Raman Narayanan here last night, the queen referred indirectly to
the hostility that continued to exist between India and Pakistan
after 50 years of their independence by calling for better ties
between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"If countries in the region share a goal and understand that by
working together they give themselves a better chance of achieving
it, then historical hostilities can be buried for good," she said
in her speech.
</P>
<P>
Her remarks, however indirect, can only lengthen the shadow
cast upon her visit by the diplomatic row between India and
Britain over Kashmir, the local press said.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic crisis arose on the eve of the queen's arrival
in India from Pakistan, the first leg of the queen's South Asia
tour.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, who is
accompanying the queen on her current tour, offered in Islamabad
to mediate on the Kashmir issue, a move which has been strongly
opposed by India.
</P>
<P>
In response to the reports, Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral,
who was visiting Egypt, reportedly said in Cairo on Saturday
evening that "a third-rate power" like Britain was "presumptuous"
in saying it had a historical responsibility to resolve the
Kashmir issue considering that it had created it in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent damage control exercise, both India and Britain
denied such reports on Monday prior to official meetings between
the queen and Indian leaders.
</P>
<P>
The queen and her husband, Prince Philip, arrived here on
Sunday night for a week-long state visit on the occasion of the
50th anniversary of India's independence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
