<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Fully Confident of China  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft will continue to lay
great importance on the Chinese market because of "the tremendous
potential of the country's market and economic development." Duh
Jia-bin, president of the Microsoft (China) Co, Ltd, said during a
recent interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
China's three million annual sales of computer and huge
intranet network that call for facilitating software, together
with adequate talents for soft and hardware development, are
favorable for the business of this largest software producer of
the world.
</P>
<P>
On September 1, four companies registered in China became
Microsoft's first authorized technological support centers. This
marked the beginning of the introduction of its global
technological support system into China.
</P>
<P>
The simultaneous launching of the Chinese and English versions
of the latest Microsoft Internet browser, Internet Explorer 4.0,
in Beijing and San Francisco ended the trend of the former
appearing later than the latter.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, Micorsoft has in the country more than
300 authorized sales agents, and a direct technological support
relationship with 30-plus software developers and 30-plus central
government organs and banks.
</P>
<P>
And to this day, 98 percent of Microsoft's employment are
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Duh attributed the achievements of Microsoft since it
established the Beijing representative office, the predecessor of
the China company, to the country's improvement of investment
climate.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he noted, the Chinese Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications will soon increase the band width of
telecommunications optical fibre to 45k.
</P>
<P>
This means the information transfer capacity of China's
telecommunications industry will be elevated to the international
advance level, Duh said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Fully Confident of China  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Duh went on to say that Microsoft takes a positive attitude
toward software piracy, an unfavorable factor in the investment
environment.
</P>
<P>
He expressed admiration for "the resolution of the Chinese
Government in promoting original software, and taking the leading
in using it."
</P>
<P>
China's efforts in cracking down on piracy have been
successful, Duh said, with pirate products reducing and the pirate
ratio dropping.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he stressed coercive measures like sanctions "are no
good to Microsoft and the Chinese partners and against the
interests of the two countries."
</P>
<P>
"I hold that economic and political issues should be
disintegrated." said Duh, who went lobbying in the US Congress this
April as member of the US Chamber of Commerce in China.
</P>
<P>
To grant China permanent most-favored-nation (MFN) trading
status and back its accession in the World Trade Organization
(WTO) are "the basis for China's competition on an equal footing
with other countries on the international arena, and an
encouragement to its further opening of the market." he added.
</P>
