<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF, Greenpeace Say Mediterranean Fish Endangered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Excessive fishing has made
swordfish and tuna endangered species in the Mediterranean,
Greenpeace and the World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) warned today.
</P>
<P>
The steady increase of fishing fleets in the Mediterranean is
drastically reducing the number of sought-after fish there, the
environmental groups said at the United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization's general council on fishing in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The growth of fishing activity by 5 to 7 percent every
year has above all reduced the population of adult tuna by 83
percent in the last 20 years, young tuna by 40 percent and
swordfish.
</P>
<P>
More than 100,000 fishermen work in the region, bringing in 1.3
million tons of fish for annual revenues of 3.8 billion U.S.
dollars, the groups said.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace and the WWF called on Mediterranean countries and
the European Commissioner in charge of fishing to stop the decline
and prevent the species' extinction.
</P>
<P>
The groups also criticized the council's work, saying it had not
done enough in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
