<HEADLINE> Venezuela, U.S. to Reduce Oil Dependence on Other Regions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela and the United
States, together with other oil producing countries in the western
hemisphere, will join efforts to help reduce the continents' oil
dependence from other regions.
</P>
<P>
This commitment was included in the energy cooperation
agreement signed by Venezuelan President Rafael Caldera and
visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton here today.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela was the first leg of Clinton's first official visit
to South America, which will also cover Brazil and Argentina. The
visit was aimed to strengthen U.S. trade cooperation with the
three countries.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Energy Secretary Federico Pena, who accompanying Clinton
during the visit, also discussed with his Venezuelan counterpart,
Erwin Arrieta, and Luis Giusti, president of the state-owned
Venezuelan Oil Company, details of the two countries' cooperation
on oil industry.
</P>
<P>
Pena said an increase in Venezuela's crude oil production would
help "reduce U.S. dependency on other oil suppliers in less stable
regions of the world."
</P>
<P>
Pena also noted that this circumstance is key and beneficial to
Venezuela, which is trying to expand its oil industry so as to
promote economic development.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela is the U.S. biggest oil supplier. Some 70 percent of
Venezuelan oil enter into the U.S. market. From January to
September this year, the country exported 1.7 million barrels of
oil to the U.S. every day.
</P>
<P>
Despite the high level of production from Mexico, Colombia,
Ecuador, Canada, Venezuela and the U.S. in the western hemisphere
still has to import a considerable oil quota from other regions in
the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
