<HEADLINE> Thai Exports Rise Sharply in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The weak baht gave Thailand's
exports a 54.14-percent year-on-year boost in September, up 15.53
percent over August this year, according to the Thai Finance
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Exports have risen each month since the Thai government cut the
baht loose on July 2, increasing in baht terms by 26.6 percent,
27.12 percent and 54.14 percent in July, August and September
respectively against the corresponding months of last year.
</P>
<P>
The baht has lost about 40 percent of its value since July.
</P>
<P>
Exports in September totaled 177 billion baht (5.05 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Exporters here were quoted today by the local press as saying
the result had been expected as the weaker baht has substantially
boosted offshore sales, especially of footwear and food products.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
