<HEADLINE> Giant-Killing Paddler Emerges from Nowhere in Table Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- To steal the limelight in the
table tennis competitions, teenager paddler Zhang Yining boasted
of a clean slate of six straight wins at the table tennis team
competitions of the Chinese Eighth National Games.
</P>
<P>
Winning the tag as a "Killer of Stars", Zhang of Beijing came
from nowhere to topple the top paddlers in the world, including
second-ranked Li Ju, former doubles world champion Qiao Hong and
seventh-ranked Yang Ying.
</P>
<P>
Ten days after her 15th birthday, the baby-faced Zhang betrayed
her elder sisters on the court with feeble looks, shyness and dumb
expressions.
</P>
<P>
Once upon the court, the Beijing native in hand-shaking grip
became surprisingly steady with her forehand and backhand loops.
</P>
<P>
"Winning over the veterans enhanced my confidence, but I myself
knew clearly that I still have a long way to go, and I will exert
every efforts to improve my rough skills in the first three
attacks," said the teenager upon a gust of praises.
</P>
<P>
"I'm a challenger without any pressure, that was the key point
for my victories over the world famous veterans," explained Zhang
who still refrained from smiling.
</P>
<P>
In the women's team finals which Jiangsu eventually won over
Beijing, Zhang strided upon the court for the opener against
doubles world champion Yang Ying of Jiangsu, the best pen-holding
woman fast attacker in the world.
</P>
<P>
Yang was seemingly to seal her game with ease after winning the
first set 21-8 through varified serves and fierce attacks.
</P>
<P>
All on a sudden, Zhang rallied back to break her rhythm by
firing a flurry of bullets towards Yang's backhand before taking
the last two games 21-18, 21-12.
</P>
<P>
En route to the finals, Zhang achieved the same feat in the
semifinals by toppling 10th-ranked Qiao Hong from one-set down
15-21, 21-8 and 23-21.
</P>
<P>
Lu Yuansheng, vice head coach of the Chinese national squad,
was generous in his praises, depicting her as a budding hopeful
with great potential.
</P>
<P>
"She has displayed strong skills in backhand attacks and
forehand loops, she is an athlete of strength and stamina,"
commented coach Lu.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing teenager started to play table tennis at an early
age of five, and was recruited into the national youth team only
in March last year.
</P>
<P>
She finished third in the singles tournament of the National
Youth Championships last year, and bagged home with the silver
medal from the Asian Junior Championships last month in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Nowsdays, Zhang Yining was on her stride along the singles
competitions wherein she has set her sights into the top eight.
</P>
<P>
To materialise her dream, Zhang faces a tough challenge to
conquer Li Ju anew. No matter whoever eventually wins, the
teenager is surely marching along her promising voyage towards the
pinnacle of her career. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
