<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bus Accident Kills 43 in Quebec </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Forty-three senior citizens were
killed and another five seriously injured when a bus plunged into
a ravine in the Canadian province of Quebec today.
</P>
<P>
The five injured were rushed to a local hospital and are
reportedly in serious condition.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred at 2:15 p.m. on Highway 138, about 100
kilometers northeast of Quebec city. The accident occurred at the
bottom of a steep hill leading into a sharp curve, police said.
</P>
<P>
Road conditions were reported to be dry and the weather
sunny. Faulty brakes are believed to be the cause of the tragedy,
police said.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien expressed shock and
sadness at the accident.
</P>
<P>
"Like all Canadians, I was horrified to learn that a pleasant
afternoon devoted to taking in the fall beauty of the Charlevoix
had ended so tragically," Chretien said in a brief statement.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time in more than 20 years that a bus
accident has occurred on the same section of highway. A 1974
accident took the lives of 13 senior citizens and injured 24.
</P>
<P>
Most of the casualties are from St-Bernard-de-Beauce, about 35
kilometers south of Quebec city. They were traveling this
Thanksgiving holiday to a ferry that would have take them to
Ile-aux-Coudres, a popular tourist spot.
</P>
<P>
This is reported to be the worst road accident in the history
of Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
