<HEADLINE> Clinton Nominates Protocol Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has nominated Mary French, his longtime Arkansas associate, head
of the State Department's protocol office.
</P>
<P>
French, the acting protocol chief, would replace Molly Raiser,
who retired in summer.
</P>
<P>
French coordinated Clinton's volunteer campaign during his 1990
gubernatorial race in Arkansas. In 1992, she helped run the
president's first inaugural and a year later became assistant
chief of protocol in the State Department's visits division.
</P>
<P>
French grew up in the farming community of Weiner just outside
Little Rock, Arkansas. She graduated from the University of
Arkansas with a degree in international studies and has been
friends with the president since his teaching days at the college
more than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
French would be responsible for advising the president and
Secretary of State on protocol matters related to all ceremonies,
dignitary visits and trips abroad involving the United States,
said Mary Masserini, a spokeswoman for the State Department's
protocol office.  
</P>
</TEXT>
