<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coach Chen Expects More Splashes from Swimming Pool </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A batch of Chinese women
swimmers displayed their prowess at the National Games, sending a
promising signal of attacks upon the world records, said Chen
Yunpeng, former head coach of the Chinese swimming national team.
</P>
<P>
"After Chen Yan broke the oldest swimming world record and Le
Jingyi swam the all-time second best on Monday, more surprises are
expected from the swimming pool at the National Games," Chen said
at the pool side.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Chen Yan clocked 4:34.79 on Monday to break the
400-meter individual medley world record, signalling the mature of
a new generation of the Chinese women swimmers, the former head
coach said.
</P>
<P>
After Petra Schneider of former East Germany set up the
previous record of 4:36.10 in 1982, a batch of Chinese swimmers
have launched serious attacks in the past 15 years, including
former Olympic champion Lin Li and former world champion Dai
Guohong.
</P>
<P>
Lin Li swam her personal best of 4:36.73 in Barcelona while Dai
Guohong clocked her best of 4:36.90 in their record-breaking bids,
all within the brink of celebration, said the world-known Chinese
swimming figure.
</P>
<P>
"The presence of Chen Yan materialised our dream to break the
oldest world record," exclaimed the former Chinese head coach.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Le Jingyi, world record holder in 50 and 100m
freestyles, was within an arm's reach to break her own 100m record
by clocking the all-time second best of 54.10 seconds on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Should she splashed the first 50 meters with more ease, which
Le covered in a span of 26.05 seconds, it's highly possible for
another world record," recalled Chen.
</P>
<P>
To put together the timings of the top four swimmers in 100m
freestyle at the National Games, their combined timing of 3:39.26
surpassed that of the American women's 100m freestyle reley of
3:42.27 this year, explained Chen.
</P>
<P>
Chen said the Chinese men swimmers also had a morale-enhancing
performance at the Games where Zeng Qiliang broke the Asian mark
in the 100-meter breaststroke by clocking the world's third best
of one minute and 1.66 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Althogh China lagged behind in the men's 200m freestyle, but
their combined results of the top four finishers at the Games
already bettered the Asian mark, the former head coach said.
</P>
</TEXT>
