<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Strives to Produce 20 Million Tons of Rice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is endeavoring to
produce 20 million tons of rice as its target in the 1997-98
fiscal year beginning April, the second year of the country's
present Five-Year Plan (1996-97 to 2000-01).
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Minister for Agriculture and Irrigation Myint Aung was
quoted by today's The New Light of Myanmar as saying five working
groups such as water supply, agricultural education and finance
have been formed to help farmers ensure success in the tasks.
</P>
<P>
Emphasis is placed on four major crops -- rice, beans and
pulses, cotton and sugarcane -- and efforts are being made to
boost the per hectare yield, the minister said at a work
coordination meeting here Monday.
</P>
<P>
He added that 16 million tons will be enough for domestic
consumption.
</P>
<P>
He also called for efforts to attract domestic and foreign
entrepreneurs to invest in cash crops such as rubber, oil palm,
jute, coffee, corn, mulberry and tea in addition to the four major
crops.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's rice output in the 1996-97 fiscal year failed to
reach the planned target of 20 million tons and its rice export
sharply decreased in the year.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the country's rice production
in the 1995-96 fiscal year was recorded at 17.95 million tons with
an export of 354,000 tons, while the output in the 1996-97 was
17.08 million tons with 93,100 tons exported.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics also show that Myanmar's rice export in
the first six months of 1997 reached merely 1,200 tons, down from
241,700 tons in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's gross domestic product grew by 5.8 percent in the
1996-97 fiscal year, in which agricultural production increased by
3.7 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
