<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Expects 6-Percent GDP Growth This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Ceylon predicted in
a recent economic report that Sri Lanka would achieve a 6-percent
gross domestic product (GDP) growth this year.
</P>
<P>
Economic indicators pointed to the potential to realize the 6-
percent growth rate projected for this year, as compared with last
year's 3.8 percent, Chandra Munasinghe, director of the bank's
Economic Research Division, was quoted by the local press today as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The division completed a study on the country's economic
situation last month.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural, forestry and fishing sectors will grow by 3.5
percent this year, according to the report of the division.
</P>
<P>
The report said that during the first seven months of this
year, the total rice output increased by 9.5 percent over a year
earlier while the output of tea, rubber and coconut also went up
by 5.4 percent, 4.7 percent and 1.1 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Textiles and garments, the leading export items of the country,
have recorded a 26.6-percent growth in the first half of this year
over the corresponding period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the GDP growth to Sri Lanka's enhanced
budget policy, power supply and surging market demand for
textiles.
</P>
<P>
It added that an increase in tourist arrivals and a declining
inflation rate also made positive contributions to the GDP growth.
</P>
<P>
Tourist arrivals during the first eight months of this year
jumped by 21.7 percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, inflation dropped from 14.7 percent in March to 12.9
percent in August. The average inflation rate for 1997 is expected
to be around 10 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
