<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Had Census Data 4,000 Years Ago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China had vital statistics as
early as the Xia Dynasty and the country's first recorded
nationwide census was conducted in 789 B.C. under the reign of
Zhou Xuan, according to materials prepared for an exhibit on
population.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, to open in Beijing on November 12, shows that
China's census reports can be traced back to Great Yu, founder of
the Xia Dynasty (circa 21st-16th century B.C.) who conducted a
successful mass campaign to control flooding in southern China
4,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Great Yu divided the country into nine regions and began to
count the number of people and the area of cultivated land.
</P>
<P>
The country's population in the Xia Dynasty was 13.5
million according to the "Records of the Later Han Dynasty
(947-950)."
</P>
<P>
After Qin Shi Huang, the first emperor of the Qin Dynasty
(221-207 B.C.), unified China, an annual nationwide census was
conducted. Materials show that in the dynasty, local authorities
reported population and tax statistics to the central imperial
government at the end of each year.
</P>
<P>
After that, feudal dynasties all paid great attention to the
census and the household registry system for the purposes of
conscription, tax-collection and requisition.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the middle of the imperial Qing Dynasty (1644-1911),
a nationwide census has been conducted in China on an annual
basis. The Chinese population of 400 million, a number often
quoted around 1949, was based on an 1835 census under Emperor
Daoguang.
</P>
<P>
The Exhibition on China's Population, at the joint sponsorship
of the Chinese State Family Planning Commission and the China
Population Association, will open to the participants of the 23rd
International Union for the Scientific Study of Population's
General Population Conference November 12-17. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
