<HEADLINE> Air China Going Public for Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Air China, China's largest
civil aviation enterprise, is restructuring into a joint-stock
company and is going public on stock exchanges both at home and
abroad, reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Yin Wenlong, president of Air China said capitalizing on the
stock market is a must for the carrier's further development.
</P>
<P>
Yin said the joint-stock restructuring will inject big capital
into the company and help it establish scientific and efficient
management systems.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the carrier, with a fleet of 65 freighters and
144 domestic and foreign air routes, is the only one allowed to
carry the Chinese national flag on its planes. Now, it is striving
to develop into a big company group.
</P>
<P>
In fact, fostering big conglomerates is an important part of
China's massive reform of its aviation industry.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, selecting good performing enterprises to go public
is another part of the major effort to reform the aviation
industry, according to Xia Xinghua, a senior official with the
Civil Aviation Administration of China.
</P>
<P>
Xia said the decision to list civil aviation firms in overseas
markets is aimed at raising funds and to place them in
international competition.
</P>
<P>
The country's two other major airlines, China Eastern Airlines
and China Southern Airlines have already been listed in both Hong
Kong and New York.  
</P>
</TEXT>
