<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Japanese Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Japanese newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
Asahi:
</P>
<P>
-- Japan's Posts and Telecommunications Ministry will
liberalize telephone rates as early as next summer in a bid to
speed up competition in the industry, as one way to spur the
country's sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
Yomiuri:
</P>
<P>
-- Mitsubishi Oil Co. is likely to be charged by the end of the
year an additional penalty tax on 6.5 billion yen in concealed
income used to provide funds to an Osaka oil dealer indicted on
bribery and other charges.
</P>
<P>
Asahi, Mainichi, Nihon Keizai:
</P>
<P>
-- The bad loan-ridden Kyoto Kyoei Bank, Japan's second largest
regional bank, will be disbanded next October.
</P>
<P>
Yomiuri, Nihon Keizai:
</P>
<P>
-- Tokyo share prices plunged broadly in Monday trading amid
incessant concerns over the strength of the economy, leaving the
market's benchmark index at its lowest level this year. 
</P>
