<HEADLINE> China, US Protecting Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- China and the United States may
soon be stepping up their wars against global warming -- with a
collective front, said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Leading officials in charge of environmental protection issues
from both countries met in Beijing yesterday to discuss the
possibility of establishing a cooperative fight against
environmental destruction.
</P>
<P>
Timothy E. Wirth, US undersecretary of state, talked about
climate change problems while meeting four Chinese ministers and
vice-ministers -- of the National Environmental Protection Agency
(NEPA), the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the State Science and
Technology Commission and the State Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
All agreed friendly cooperation, based on equality between the
two nations, is a significant component in solving the serious
global environmental problem.
</P>
<P>
Global warming is the potential increase in temperature of the
earth's atmosphere caused by the greenhouse effect.
</P>
<P>
The US is currently the top offender, discharging 22 percent of
the world's total greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
China, with 14 percent, is second. However, China's per capita
consumption is only about ten percent of that of the US, NEPA
statistics indicate.
</P>
<P>
Wirth, who arrived in Beijing on Sunday, arranged the two-day
visit to try and explore ways of co-operating with Chinese
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Wirth expressed a desire to establish an agreement with Chinese
government officials regarding technology transfer and financing
China's effort in developing efficient energy sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
