<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tariff Cut Mobilizes WTO Entry, Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The newest round of autonomous
cuts in China's customs duties will not only speed up its pace to
join in the process of global economic integrity, but also help
deepen its on-going State enterprise reform, today's "China Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
As of October 1 this year, 73 percent of the 6,633 tariff items
have been cut significantly. The average tariff rate fell from 23
percent to 17 percent. This is a drop of 26 percent, which means
that tariffs have come down by 60.6 percent since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Since 1986, when China began its bid to resume signatory status
in the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (Gatt), the country
has made unremitting efforts to overhaul its economic system and
become more integrated into the world economy.
</P>
<P>
By December 1993, the average tariff level had been brought
down to 36.4 percent from 43.2 percent in 1992. It was further cut
to 23 percent in April 1996. And in 1995, Chinese President Jiang
Zemin declare China would reduce its average tarifflevel to 15
percent by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The large-scale tariff cut will increase the market
competitiveness of imported products and provides the opportunity
for breaking the impasse of restructuring State enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Domestic enterprises have only two options: Either to go
bankrupt due to loss of market share, or the face up to the
challenge and survive, Zhang Hanya, an associate professor at the
University of International Business and Economics, was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
State-owned properties and other social capital will be
reorganized through association, merger, leasing, contract
operation, shareholding, the joint stock co-operative system or
sell-off.
</P>
<P>
That will cause a whole succession of changes in the
property-rights system, the management mechanism and social
security arrangements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
