<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, IMF Discuss Solution to Financial Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
been holding closed-door meetings with the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) and the World Bank here in an effort to seek solution
to the financial difficulty faced by the country.
</P>
<P>
Part of the talks concerns improving the financial and real
estate sectors, both of which have been hard hit by the currency
turmoil since July, Deputy Assistant Minister for Economic,
Finance and Development Supervision Miranda S. Goeltom said last
night.
</P>
<P>
Goeltom said the first stage of the talks, which began Monday,
has yet to enter into details, such as the possible liquidation of
troubled banks.
</P>
<P>
"We don't know concrete results of the talks yet," she said.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the IMF team met with Bank Indonesia (central
bank) Governor Soedradjad Djiwandono Monday, but the substance of
their discussions was not revealed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the sources said, the Monetary Council held a
meeting Monday which was related to the government's decision to
seek assistance from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government decided last Wednesday to seek help
from international bodies such as the IMF, the World Bank and the
Asian Development Bank to improve the country's economy after the
rupiah's value dropped by as much as 46 percent against the U.S.
dollar since last January.
</P>
<P>
The IMF and the World Bank responded to Indonesia's move
positively and sent a team to Jakarta last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah recovered last Friday from 3,650 against the dollar
to 3,355/65 following the government's decision.
</P>
<P>
However, the currency dropped to 3,625 against the dollar at
midday on Monday before recovering in the afternoon to close at
3,470/80.
</P>
<P>
A currency dealer said the rupiah recovered because Bank
Indonesia intervened in the market by selling some dollars.
</P>
<P>
Economists and analysts here said talks between Indonesian
officials and IMF teams had checked the rupiah's fall as the
market was waiting for the IMF financial package.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Finance Minister Mar'ie Mumammad said earlier that
the result of the talks between Indonesia and the IMF would be
possible within two and three weeks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
