<HEADLINE> Prodi Close to Ending Government Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Italy's caretaker Prime Minister
Romano Prodi said here today that the four-day government crisis
is expected to end since he is very close to reaching an agreement
with the Communist Refoundation Party in his center-left coalition.
</P>
<P>
"We are close to an agreement," Prodi said, who met Communist
Refoundation leader Fausto Bertinotti earlier today.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Refoundation Party last Thursday withdrew from
the parliamentary majority supporting the government by refusing
to back the 1998 deficit-cutting budget proposed by Prodi, forcing
the prime minister to resign.
</P>
<P>
Intensive negotiations aimed at patching up the alliance began
soon after Prodi's resignation.
</P>
<P>
"The talks are going satisfactorily," Prodi said as he emerged
from the Quirinal Palace, after reporting to the President Oscar
Luigi Scalfaro on the talks with the communists.
</P>
<P>
Bertinotti also said late on Monday that a deal was imminent
and his party would vote for Prodi's controversial 1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the budget bill would be changed in order to
accommodate Communist Refoundation's demands, Prodi said, "No, the
budget will remain as it is."
</P>
<P>
The budget is part of Italy's efforts on meeting the Maastricht
Treaty criteria for joining the European single currency among the
first group in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Although unwilling to reveal details of a likely accord, Prodi
said it would be "for all of 1998", and hinted that it could
possibly be extended further until the present legislature expires
in 2001.
</P>
<P>
Once an agreement is reached, Scalfaro, who is to conclude
political consultations on the crisis on Tuesday, is expected to
send Prodi back to the Chamber of Deputies to ask for a vote of
confidence in his government.
</P>
<P>
The budget has to be ratified by the end of this year, after
passing through a series of parliamentary committees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
