<HEADLINE> Indonesian Inflation Estimated at 7.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's inflation rate this
year is estimated at 7.4 percent and it will not rise to 10
percent or higher, according to the Central Bureau of Statistics
(BPS).
</P>
<P>
BPS chief Soegito said here Monday that even though there were
a prolonged drought and a currency crisis, the inflation rate
would not go up to or exceed 10 percent, Antara News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"If we are serious in handling the food problem resulting from
the long drought, I am convinced that the inflation rate will
reach only about 7 percent," he said after reporting to President
Soeharto at the Bina Graha Presidential Office.
</P>
<P>
Soegito said that inflation in September was 1.29 percent and
that the cumulative inflation rate between January and September
this year had thus reached 5.37 percent.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate during the same period of last year was 4.94
percent.
</P>
<P>
On the country's economic growth, Soegito said the figure this
year could be around 7 percent as compared with 7.98 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
However, some government officials said earlier that
Indonesia's economic growth this year will be 5 to 6 percent due
to its currency turmoil and prolonged drought.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah, the country's currency, has dropped by 46 percent
against the U.S. dollar since the beginning of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
