<HEADLINE> US Official Explaining Energy Development Plan at 15th WPC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- While much has changed in the
world petroleum marketplace, the United States will continue to
have a foot in two camps, that is, one in the camp of producing
nations, and the other in the consuming nations, said a senior US
energy official.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ministerial panel of the 15th World Petroleum
Congress (WPC) here today, Robert S. Kripowicz, principal deputy
assistant secretary for fossil energy of the US Department of
Energy, said that the oil and gas industry continues to be a
significant and crucial component of the American economy.
</P>
<P>
The oil and gas industry accounts for almost 5 percent of the
country's gross output, or about 360 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The US official added that the US is continuing to discover
significant amounts of oil and gas, particularly in the Gulf of
Mexico, and current projections show natural gas production
increasing by more than 40 percent by 2015.
</P>
<P>
He told the ministerial panel that the US is the world's
largest user of petroleum and also the world's largest importer,
dependent on imports for 50 percent of consumption.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three decades, the US has established the
Strategic Petroleum Reserve (SPR) to safeguard economy in case of
future oil supply disruptions, he said. Currently, the SPR
contains 563 million barrels of crude oil, he added.
</P>
<P>
The globalization of the oil and gas industry is becoming a
trend, the US energy official noted. The US oil and gas companies
have markedly increased their overseas presence, often partnership
with foreign companies or governments, and the US has developed
oil and gas cooperation with energy companies from Norway, Japan,
United Kingdom, China and other nations.
</P>
<P>
Increasingly, global leaders and business executives are
incorporating environmental protection into their development
plans, and the world's people expect a clean and healthy
environment as well as economic well-being, Kripowicz said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
