<HEADLINE> India Trying to Narrow Gap Between Oil Demand, Supply: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- India is taking vigorous steps
to increase oil and gas exploration and production, so as to meet
the challenge of growing gap between demand and domestic supply,
said Janeshwar Mishra, Minister for Petroleum and Natural Gas.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ministerial panel of the ongoing 15th World
Petroleum Congress (WPC) here today, the senior Indian official
noted that India has taken several steps and announced new policy
initiatives, including the New Exploration Licensing Policy aimed
at providing a major thrust to accelerate exploration and
production activity through the involvement of private sector and
providing open access to exploration acreages.
</P>
<P>
Under the initiatives, the official said, a large number of
oil exploration blocks are being offered on terms and conditions
which rank among the most attractive in the world.
</P>
<P>
In addition, India has been actively pursuing exploration and
production opportunities abroad. In this regard, the Middle East,
former Soviet Union, Africa and South East Asia have been areas of
key interest and focus, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He told the ministerial panel that to meet the enormous demand
of petroleum products, India has emerged as one of the largest
centers for establishing new refineries which are being set up either
by the national oil companies, joint ventures or private companies.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he added, the refining capacity in the country is
going to increase from the present level of 62 million tons per
annum to over 170 million tons per annum by the year 2006.  
</P>
</TEXT>
