<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmer Invests Personal Assets in Hometown Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A farmer of east China's Fujian
Province has made newspaper headlines by financing a wholesale
market in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jianchun, 39, of Fengting township, Xianyou county, has
injected an impressive six million yuan from his personal assets
in the first phase of the market, which involves an investment of
28 million yuan (3.337 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Completed recently, the project also involves World Bank loans
worth 16 million yuan, in addition to 6 million yuan from other
local farmers.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who made his fortune by dealing in dried fruits, decided
on the investment after becoming convinced that the project would
be lucrative.
</P>
<P>
Fengting, a coastal area in central Fujian, is a seaport and
near two other ports and a national highway leading to Fuzhou and
Xiamen. "Fengting township can deal in 10 containers of dried
fruit every year," Chen said. "I'm sure it will become a major
distribution center linking the coast with inland areas."
</P>
<P>
Spurred by a state policy to encourage private enterprises, the
Fujian Provincial Planning Committee endorsed Chen's investment in
the market, which is expected to become one of the 10 largest in
the province.
</P>
<P>
Chen's Xianyou Agricultural, Industrial and Trade Wholesale
Market, designed to house four markets for fruit, aquatic
products, farm produce and handicrafts, will need a total
investment of 55 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The first phase with five trading buildings of stalls and
offices began operations early this month.
</P>
<P>
"To attract traders, I'll not charge stall fees in the first
year, " Wang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
