<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. President Ends Visit to Venezuela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela and the U.S. should
further expand their traditional cooperation in the future,
visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton and his Venezuelan
counterpart, Rafael Caldera, said in a joint statement today.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued here before Clinton's departure for
Brazil, the second stop of his first official visit to South
America.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the two presidents expressed satisfaction
over the bilateral relations and stressed the importance of
expanding trade and investment so as to improve living standards
for peoples of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Caldera and Clinton also committed themselves to support the
creation of a free trade zone comprising North and South Americas
by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of countries in both America are expected to discuss
the issue in next year's Santiago summit in Chile.
</P>
<P>
During his 24-hour visit to Venezuela, Clinton signed with
Caldera five agreements on cooperation in energy, science,
technology, customs and drug control.
</P>
<P>
They also signed a memorandum of understanding on cooperation
in logistics.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is the fourth U.S. president who has visited Venezuela,
following John F. Kennedy in 1961, James Carter in 1978 and George
Bush in 1990. He will also visit Brazil and Argentina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
