<HEADLINE> Algeria Eyes for Greater Role in World Energy Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A senior Algerian official said
here today that his country is striving for a greater role in the
world energy industry.
</P>
<P>
Algeria wants to develop partnership with other countries in
the hydrocarbon sector, which is "a strategic option and not only
management style", Youcef Yousfi, minister of energy and mines,
said at the ministerial panel of the ongoing 15th World Petroleum
Congress Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to emphasize on the dynamic role of my country, in
its quest to be among the players in the energy industry, not only
in the region but definitely on a global vision," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our opinion is that tomorrow-world is calling for an increased
cooperation based on complementarity and mutual support," he added.
</P>
<P>
Petroleum resources are the key element of the Algerian economy,
contributing more than 90 percent of the nation's total exports.
</P>
<P>
The country, among the world's top 20 in oil and gas reserves, is
one of the biggest exporters of condensate and liquified petroleum
gas, and ranks the fourth in natural gas export worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Youcef Yousfi went on to say that partnership in the
hydrocarbon sector has led to a tremendous boost to the industry
for the past ten years, with a number of international oil service
companies established in the country.
</P>
<P>
The minister expected that a total investment of 20 billion U.S.
dollars will be injected to the Algerian oil industry in the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
"Our government is committed with a continuous progress of the
hydrocarbon sector and is expressing its full support for the
increasing exploration and development activities," Yousfi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
