<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, October 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Britain's B.A.T. Industries, the world's second
largest cigarette manufacturer, is discussing with Zurich Group
for a 32 billion U.S. dollar merger to get rid of its burdensome
link with the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
B.A.T. has decided to let the tobacco portion to survive on its
own and fold the U.S. and British insurance companies into the
financial businesses owned by Zurich Group, the New York Times
reported Monday. (BC-UK-B.A.T. Merger)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- Over 4,000 small-scale miners in northwest
Tanzania's Shinyanga District have been ordered to stop mining
diamond at Maganzo Village.
</P>
<P>
The miners, who were accused of causing serious environmental
destruction to the village's arable land since last year, have
been ordered to stop mining activities immediately and cover all
pits in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The ban, effective last Saturday, was given by the Shinyanga
District Commissioner, Simon Massaga, Daily News reported
Monday. (BC-Tanzania-Diamond)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA -- The Federal Supreme Court of Ethiopia Monday
ruled out the appeal by lawyers either for the dismissal of the
case against former Deputy Prime Minister Tamirat Layne and his
accomplices or their acquittal, the Ethiopian News Agency reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme court, citing article 63 of the procedural law of
the Penal Code, said it has no mandate to grant bail to a
defendant who might face a rigorous imprisonment of about 15
years. (BC-Ethiopia-Supreme Court)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan decided
Monday to appoint Benon V. sevan, a national of Cyprus as the
Executive Director of the Office of the Iraq Program, effective
October 15, 1997, said a statement issued Monday by the
spokesman's office.
</P>
<P>
Since July 1994, Mr. Sevan has been serving as the Assistant
Secretary-General for Conference and support Services and United
Nations Security Council Coordinator, and will continue to carry
out the latter function. (BC-Annan-Sevan-Appointments)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister Jawad Anani said
Monday that Jordan had slackened its security cooperation with
Israel over the Mashaal affair.
</P>
<P>
Anani said in an interview with Israel Radio that security
staff in Israeli Embassy in Amman had been decreased at Jordan's
request following the assassination attempt of Khaled Mashaal, a
Hamas leader in Jordan. (BC-Israel-Jordan-Security Ties)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON - - British Prime Minister Tony Blair met Sinn Fein
leader Gerry Adams Monday, the first encounter between a British
prime minister and Irish Republican leader since 1921, according
to reports from Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Blair's decision to meet Adams has drawn fierce criticism from
Northern Irish Protestant leaders and political opponents in
London.
</P>
<P>
David Trimble, the Ulster Unionist Party leader, expressed pity
for a prime minister to meet the head of "a terrorist
organization" that had killed so many British soldiers, policemen
and civilians and had still not forsworn violence. (BC-UK-Sinn
Fein)
</P>
<P>
