<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Enhance Cooperation With Central Asian Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine hopes to start energy and
transport cooperation with Kazakhstan and Kirghizstan, a senior
Ukrainian official announced today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Nikolay Doroshenko, head of the
CIS Affairs Department attached to the presidential office, said
Ukraine expects to initiate cooperation on oil extraction and
processing with Kazakhstan and to import oil and natural gas from
that Central Asian country.
</P>
<P>
Besides helping Kazakhstan with construction of oil pipeline,
Kiev proposed technologies to help modernize Kazakh enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Doroshenko added that Ukraine is considering to participate in
the transport project that will link Europe, Ukraine, Kazakhstan
and China together.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine also hopes to set up cooperation on energy,
particularly on hydraulic power, with Kirghizstan, Doroshenko
noted. Kiev plans to offer construction materials and technologies
in exchange for natural gas.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma will visit Kazakhstan and
Kighizstan on the coming two days.
</P>
<P>
As an energy-starved nation, Ukraine imports 70 percent of its
energy from Russia since its independence in 1991. This has badly
hurt Ukraine's economy. To lesson its reliance on Moscow, Ukraine
has to turn to Central Asian nations for alternative power
supply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA to Probe into Rome Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The International Football
Federation (FIFA) said on Monday it is now probing into the
violence between English and Italian fans at Saturday's World Cup
qualifier.
</P>
<P>
FIFA General Secretary Sepp Blatter said in Zurich that neither
England nor Italy are in danger of being ousted from next year's
World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the draw for the World Cup play-offs, Blatter said
that FIFA would wait for their investigations to be completed
before deciding whether any punishment was necessary.
</P>
<P>
But he confirmed that expulsion was not one of the options.
</P>
<P>
Fans from both countries were involved with clashes with
Italian riot police during and after the match drawn goalless
between England and Italy.
</P>
<P>
England qualified for the finals in France and Italy was
dragged into a two-leg play-off against Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
