<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers published today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad has launched a
bitter tirade against the developed world, accusing it of
practicing a form of "modern colonialism," as Indonesian officials
last night met International Monetary Fund and World Bank
representatives to discuss a reported 12 billion U.S. dollar
credit facility to restore investor confidence in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Voters are shunning the federal government and its Labor
opposition, which are formed by the country's major parties, with
a new Herald poll showing almost one in every four voters
nationally is prepared to vote with independents or minor parties.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- The National Gallery of Victoria trustees last night
defended the gallery's Director Timonthy Potts as he came under
fierce criticism for canceling the exhibition of Piss Christ, a
controversial depiction of a crucifix in urine by American
photographer Andres Serrano.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Australia's News Corporation and the country's biggest
telecommunications company Telstra are gearing up for a major
legal showdown with the federal government's competition watchdog
attempting to save the 460 million U.S. dollar merger of Australis
Media Ltd. and Foxtel.  
</P>
</TEXT>
