<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Population Statistics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A former Deputy-director of
China's State Statistics Bureau says that carefully-designed
methods and a strict control mechanism have kept China's
population statistics "accurate and credible".
</P>
<P>
Sun Jingxin, who is now a vice president of the China
Population Association (CPA) and a member of the State Family
Planning Commission advisory board, told a conference on
population science in Beijing that census statistics were obtained
in three stages: correction of household registration; household
visits and correction; and post-correction checks; with a certain
number of errors corrected in each stage.
</P>
<P>
In the fourth census conducted in 1990, during the two weeks of
census calculation and post-calculation checks, the five million
census takers were responsible for about 300 people each.
</P>
<P>
In addition to checks by other census takers, residents often
took part in checking to make the figures more accurate, and as a
result, a post-census sample check gave an error of 0.6 per
thousand, far below the one percent allowed in statistics, Sun
says.
</P>
<P>
He said that there were strict quality control at each stage of
the census, and sample checks were made at each stage.
</P>
<P>
"Quality checking teams were established from the provincial
level down to the neighborhood, whose responsibility was to
collect and review the data to prevent systematic errors on a
large scale," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He did say that new challenges have arisen, with the biggest
problem coming from the surge in the number of migrant workers
moving from the countryside to cities.
</P>
<P>
To counter this, Sun suggests the use of population maps made
from computer-processed photos taken from the air, which show all
houses, roads and fields, for future censuses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
