<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> T Cell Kills HIV-Infected Cells </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 13 (Xinhua) -- A team of U.S. scientists has
demonstrated killing of human immune-deficiency virus (HIV)
infected cells in laboratory studies using immune system T Cells,
the California-based Cell Genesys Inc. reported today.
</P>
<P>
The T cells are genetically engineered to seek out and destroy
HIV-infected cells.
</P>
<P>
They have been proved to be able to target and kill infected
cells as efficiently and early as naturally occurring HIV-specific
T cells which are lost during the early stages of HIV infection,
the company said through wire service.
</P>
<P>
The scientists believe that they have identified an important
new treatment strategy for AIDS based on their findings in the
study.
</P>
<P>
Cell Genesys is currently conducting Phase II human clinical
trials in AIDS gene therapy. The study will help determine
whether the company's gene therapy can reduce the requirement for
long-term treatment with combinations of three or more antiviral
drugs.
</P>
<P>
In the Phase I trial, no treatment-related safety problems were
observed, and the data showed that the modified cells persisted in
the circulatory system for up to nine months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
