<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Reform Should Proceed Without Social Obligations: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The social obligations of postal
administrations should not be ignored in the race for greater
commercial freedom, said decision-makers attending a Universal
Postal Union (UPU) high level meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
The biggest challenge for the postal service is one facing
government, UPU International Bureau Director General Thomas
Leavey told delegates.
</P>
<P>
Present at the two-day summit on October 13-14 are more than
500 ministers and chief executives of postal administrations of
the UPU's 189 members as well as representatives of diplomatic
missions and international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Governments need to find a balance between giving postal
services greater freedom to operate competitively but at the same
time to serve broader social interests, Leavey said.
</P>
<P>
Postal services are part of global business and if they behave
in a business-like manner, they can be assured of continued growth
and a prosperous future, Leavey said. "The letter will not
disappear," Leavey said with confidence.
</P>
<P>
A recent UPU study has predicted a growth of 2.5 percent per
year in letter volumes worldwide between now and 2005. However,
despite real growth in physical mail volumes, providers of mail
services are actually losing overall market share because of
modern technological advances, a diversion to electronic media and
growing competition from other service providers. The market share
for physical mail is projected to drop from 20 percent now to 15
percent by 2005.
</P>
<P>
In a keynote address today, Chief Executive of New Zealand Post
Elmar Toime said that if postal services are to survive, they
should get rid of their fear of deregulation and competition. He
stressed the need for business decisions, made on the basis of
both commercial and national interests.
</P>
<P>
Modern electronic communications hold new business
opportunities for postal services as good purchases across the
Internet still need to be delivered, Toime explained. He expressed
the hope that the reform process in the postal world will be
completed by the year 2005 and that the postal world will enjoy
commercial freedom and customer confidence.
</P>
<P>
China's Deputy Minister of Posts and Telecommunications Liu
Liqing is the conference chairman. In his opening address, Liu
said, "Over the recent years, the postal market has undergone
profound changes and competition is intensifying with each passing
day, bringing severe trials and challenges to postal sectors of
all countries." He hoped that experience and ideas will be shared
and superb opportunities be explored so as to find answers to
questions like how to better adapt to the market demand and deepen
the reform and how members should cooperate to achieve common
development.
</P>
<P>
The debate will continue as the postal world prepares for the
next Universal Postal Congress to be held in Beijing in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
