<DOCNO> XIE19971014.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Troops Start Pullback from Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has started to withdraw
from northern Iraq its troops participating in the last operation
against Kurdish militants, the Anatolia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
It quoted senior Turkish military sources as saying thousands
of troops returned to southeastern Turkey early this morning,
after the main goal of the operation has been achieved.
</P>
<P>
About 15,000 Turkish troops, backed by jets and artillery fire,
stormed into northern Iraq late last month to strike the militants
of outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the General Staff of the Turkish Armed
Forces showed that 816 rebels have been killed during this round
of military operation. Meanwhile, Turkish troops suffered
casualties of 15 killed and 58 wounded.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has in recent years frequently launched cross-border
military operations into northern Iraq in an attempt to wipe out
the PKK rebels taking shelter there.
</P>
<P>
The military sources said that an unspecified number of Turkish
troops will remain in the area to prevent a comeback of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's military operations have triggered strong protests
from Iran and some Arab countries, which urged Turkey to respect
Iraq's sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Ankara, however, contended that its operations have been aimed
at rooting up the PKK rebels, whom it accused of posing a serious
threat to the security of its border areas.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a war against the Turkish government
since 1984 in a bid to establish an independent Kurdish state in
southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
